thorlink= |year=2003|place=Jefferson, N.C. |publisher=McFarland & Co|isbn=9780786414802|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q0GHlSxUGEMC}}\n* {{cite news|ref=harv|last = Thorp |first = Gene |title = First Civil War Deaths Took Place in Baltimore | newspaper = Washington Post\n|pages =  |language =  |publisher = |date = April 19, 2011  |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/house-divided/post/first-civil-war-deaths-took-place-in-baltimore/2011/04/18/AFeOpQ4D_blog.html | access-date = June 11, 2017 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last = Wills|first = Brian S. |title = The War Hits Home: The Civil War in Southeastern Virginia |authorlink= |year=2001 |origyear= |place=Charlottesville |publisher=University Press of Virginia |isbn=9780813920276 |url=https://archive.org/details/warhitshomecivil0000will|url-access=registration}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n[[Category:Massachusetts Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1864]]\n", "name_user": "Buffalohead", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/6th_Regiment_Massachusetts_Volunteer_Militia"}
{"title_page": "Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis", "text_new": "{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n'''Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis''', is an American neuroscientist and principal investigator at the [[Rowland Institute for Science|Rowland Institute]] at [[Harvard University]]. Her lab investigates the neural basis of adaptive motor behaviors in mice to inform future translational research in neurological diseases. {{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Rowland Institute at Harvard University\n| alma_mater        = University of Oregon, Harvard University\n| known_for         = DeepLabCut deep learning software for animal pose estimation\n| awards            = Ernest Peralta Fund Award, Rowland Junior Fellowship, Women & the Brain (WATB) Fellowship for Advancement in Brain Science, CZI Essential Open Source Software for Science - grant for DeepLabCut, ELLIS Society Fellow, Natural Intelligence, Mind, Brain & Behavior Harvard University Faculty Award, eLife Travel Grant Award Winner, NVIDIA GPU Grant\n| Institutions      = Rowland Institute at Harvard University\n}}\n== Early life and education ==\nMathis conducted her undergraduate education at the [[University of Oregon]] receiving a bachelors of science in 2007.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/team|title=People|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> She then worked as a senior research technician and lab manager at the Project A.L.S. Laboratory for Stem Cell Research at [[Columbia University]] from 2007 to 2012.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.harvard.edu/mwamoroso/home|title=Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis|website=scholar.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Working under the mentorship of Dr. Christopher E. Henderson and Dr. [[Hynek Wichterle]], Mathis modelled [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]] (A.L.S.) using [[stem cell]]-derived motor neurons.<ref name=\"auto5\"/> During her time in the lab, she published a first author scientific paper in the [[The Journal of Neuroscience|Journal of Neuroscience]] which offered a novel protocol for generating human limb-innervating neural subtypes in vitro for use in neurological disease research.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Amoroso|first=Mackenzie W.|last2=Croft|first2=Gist F.|last3=Williams|first3=Damian J.|last4=O'Keeffe|first4=Sean|last5=Carrasco|first5=Monica A.|last6=Davis|first6=Anne R.|last7=Roybon|first7=Laurent|last8=Oakley|first8=Derek H.|last9=Maniatis|first9=Tom|last10=Henderson|first10=Christopher E.|last11=Wichterle|first11=Hynek|date=2013-01-09|title=Accelerated high-yield generation of limb-innervating motor neurons from human stem cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23303937|journal=The Journal of Neuroscience: The Official Journal of the Society for Neuroscience|volume=33|issue=2|pages=574\u2013586|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.0906-12.2013|issn=1529-2401|pmc=3711539|pmid=23303937}}</ref> Mathis then moved to Boston and joined the graduate program in molecular and cellular biology (MCB) at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On her way to completing her PhD, she also completed a master's degree.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/> During her PhD, Mathis conducted research on the neural circuits underlying reward prediction errors under the mentorship of Dr. [[Naoshige Uchida]] at the Harvard Center for Brain Science.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In her first year as a graduate student, Mathis received an [[National Science Foundation|National Science Foundation Fellowship]] to fund her graduate research.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/archive/four-mcb-graduate-students-receive-nsf-fellowships-in-2013/|title=FOUR MCB GRADUATE STUDENTS RECEIVE NSF FELLOWSHIPS IN 2013|date=2013-04-11|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Mathis was able to merge her interests in motor control with Uchida's expertise in large scale neural recordings and behavioral analysis to forge a new scientific direction in the lab<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and publish a first author paper in [[Neuron (journal)|Neuron]] by the end of her PhD regarding the essential role played by the [[somatosensory cortex]] in forelimb [[motor adaptation]] in rodents.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mathis|first=Mackenzie Weygandt|last2=Mathis|first2=Alexander|last3=Uchida|first3=Naoshige|date=2017-03-22|title=Somatosensory Cortex Plays an Essential Role in Forelimb Motor Adaptation in Mice|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627317301575|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=93|issue=6|pages=1493\u20131503.e6|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2017.02.049|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Following her PhD, Mathis was awarded the Rowland Junior Fellowship which provided five years of funding to start her own lab at Harvard's Rowland Institute in Cambridge, MA.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Prior to founding the Mathis Lab at Harvard, Mathis was awarded the [http://womenandthebrain.org/ Women & the Brain] (WATB) Fellowship for Advancement in Brain Science which provided her with the funding to bridge the gap between her PhD skills and her independent career goals through postdoctoral work in [[Germany]] under the mentorship of [[Matthias Bethge]]\u2019s at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In her postdoctoral work, Mathis focused on pioneering [[deep learning]] tools for neural and behavioral analysis which served as a critical step towards her independent career.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mathis|first=Alexander|last2=Mamidanna|first2=Pranav|last3=Abe|first3=Taiga|last4=Cury|first4=Kevin M.|last5=Murthy|first5=Venkatesh N.|last6=Mathis|first6=Mackenzie W.|last7=Bethge|first7=Matthias|date=2018-04-09|title=Markerless tracking of user-defined features with deep learning|url=http://arxiv.org/abs/1804.03142|journal=arXiv:1804.03142 [cs, q-bio, stat]}}</ref>\n\n== Career and research ==\nIn 2017, Mathis started her lab at the [[Rowland Institute for Science|Rowland Institute]] at [[Harvard University]] with a goal of reverse engineering neural circuits that drive adaptive motor behavior.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Through large-scale neural recordings and building novel robotic and machine learning tools, the [http://www.mousemotorlab.org/ Mathis Lab] probes neural circuits and analyzes behavioral outputs to better understand how brain function relates to behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brain.harvard.edu/?people=mackenzie-mathis|title=Mackenzie Mathis|website=Harvard Brain Science Initiative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Mathis is dedicated to the concept of [[open science]]<ref name=\"auto7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologynetworks.com/neuroscience/articles/interview-a-deeper-cut-into-behavior-with-mackenzie-mathis-327618|title=Interview: A Deeper Cut Into Behavior With Mackenzie Mathis|website=Neuroscience from Technology Networks|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and as such, the novel [[deep learning]] tool she designed, in collaboration with Dr. Alexander Mathis, is [[open access]] such that researchers worldwide have access to the code in order to use this tool to analyze animal behaviors in an unbiased and precise way to inform a better understanding of how neural activity drives specific behaviors.<ref name=\"auto7\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=c823ad30-6ec7-11ea-bf9b-c9cdf6e03cf3&url=L25ld3MvZmVhdHVyZXMvMjAxOS0wNi0xOC9hcHBsZS1nb29nbGUtYW5kLWZhY2Vib29rLWFyZS1yYWlkaW5nLWFuaW1hbC1yZXNlYXJjaC1sYWJz|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/deeplabcut-tracking-animal-movements/564338/|title=A Game-Changing AI Tool for Tracking Animal Movements|last=Yong|first=Ed|date=2018-07-03|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The deep learning tool designed by Mathis is called [http://www.mousemotorlab.org/deeplabcut DeepLabCut]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/deeplabcut|title=DeepLabCut|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> which relies on [[transfer learning]] to optimize an existing [[neural network]] to a desired dataset after sufficient training.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Mathis has shown the versatility of this tool on many diverse datasets highlighting the robust design and potential for wide use in fields even beyond neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2018/08/an-open-source-ai-tool-available-to-study-movement-across-behaviors-and-species/|title=An open-source AI tool available to study movement across behaviors and species|date=2018-08-30|website=Harvard Gazette|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Mathis announced that she would be moving to the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|Swiss Federal Institute of Technology]], working within the Brain Mind Institute & Center for Neuroprosthetics (<nowiki>http://www.mousemotorlab.org/#research</nowiki>) as a tenure-track professor.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/|title=adaptive motor control lab|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"auto8\">{{Cite journal|last=Evangelista|first=Sandy|date=2019-09-27|title=Nominations of EPFL professors|url=https://actu.epfl.ch/news/nominations-of-epfl-professors-135/|language=en}}</ref> The lab will be moving to [[Campus Biotech]] in [[Geneva|Geneva, Switzerland]] in the summer of 2020, where Mathis will hold the Bertarelli Foundation Chair of Integrative Neuroscience.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/news|title=News|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"auto8\"/>\u00a0\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n* 2019 - 2020 CZI Essential Open Source Software for Science - grant for DeepLabCut<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chanzuckerberg.com/eoss/proposals/|title=CZI \u2013 Essential Open Source Software for Science|website=Chan Zuckerberg Initiative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n* 2019 ELLIS Society Fellow, Natural Intelligence<ref name=\"auto\"/> \n* 2018 Mind, Brain & Behavior Harvard University Faculty Award \n* 2018 eLife Travel Grant Award Winner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elifesciences.org/inside-elife/1b397041/early-career-researcher-travel-grants-2018-first-seven-authors-selected|title=Early-career researcher travel grants 2018: First seven authors selected|date=2018-04-03|website=eLife|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n* 2017 NVIDIA GPU Grant<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 2017 - 2022 Rowland Fellowship<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 2017 Women & the Brain Fellowship for Advancement of Neuroscience<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bethgelab.org/home/funding/|title=BETHGE LAB \u00b7 Funding|website=bethgelab.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2013 - 2018 National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship Life Sciences \u2013 Neuroscience<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 2013, \u201914, \u201916 Harvard University Certificate of Distinction in Teaching (MCB80, MCB145)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/tag/awards/|title=awards Archives|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2014 Dr. Ernest Peralta Fund Award for Best Qualifying Exam proposal & defense, Harvard<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/tag/ernest-peralta-fund-award/|title=Ernest Peralta Fund Award Archives|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2012 - 2013 Morris E. Zukerman Graduate Fellowship - awarded to top students in brain sciences at Harvard GSAS<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n== Publications ==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=IhqY9XgAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Mackenzie W. Mathis - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n* '''Mathis MW''', Mathis A, Uchida N. Somatosensory Cortex Plays an Essential Role in Forelimb Motor Adaptation in Mice, '''''Neuron.''''' 2017. 10.1016/j.neuron.2017.02.049. \n* Ho R, Sances S, Gowing G, '''Amoroso, MW''', et al. ALS disrupts spinal motor neuron maturation and aging pathways within gene co-expression networks. '''''Nature Neuroscience''','' 2016.\n* Li H, Kuwajima T, Oakley D, et al. Protein Prenylation Constitutes an Endogenous Brake on Axonal Growth. '''''Cell Reports'''''. 2016.16 (2) :545 - 558. \n* Cohen JY, '''Amoroso MW''', Uchida N. Serotonergic neurons signal reward and punishment on multiple timescales. '''''eLife'''''. 2015. 10.7554/eLife.06346\n* Re D B, Le Verche V, Yu C, '''Amoroso, MW''', \u00a0et al. Necroptosis Drives Motor Neuron Death in Models of Both Sporadic and Familial ALS. '''''Neuron'''''. 2014. 81 :1001 - 1008. \n* '''Amoroso MW''', Croft GF, Williams DJ, et al. Accelerated High-Yield Generation of Limb-Innervating Motor Neurons from Human Stem Cells. '''''Journal of Neuroscience.''''' 2013. 33 (2) :574 - 586.\n* N\u00e9delec S, Peljto M, Shi P, et al. Concentration-Dependent Requirement for Local Protein Synthesis in Motor Neuron Subtype-Specific Response to Axon Guidance Cues. '''''Journal of Neuroscience''''', 2012. 32 (4) :1496 - 1506. \n* Takazawa T, Croft GF, '''Amoroso MW''', et al. Maturation of Spinal Motor Neurons Derived from Human Embryonic Stem Cells. '''''PLOS ONE''''', 2012. 7 (7) :e40154. \n* Boulting GL*, Kiskinis E*, Croft GF*, '''Amoroso, MW*''', Oakley, D* et al. A functionally characterized test set of human induced pluripotent stem cells. '''''Nature Biotechnology''''', 2011. 29 (3) :279 - 286. \n* Bock C, Kiskinis E, Verstappen G, et al. Reference Maps of human ES and iPS cell variation enable high-throughput characterization of pluripotent cell lines. '''''Cell''''', 2011.144 (3) :439 - 452.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMathis is currently married to neuroscientist Dr. Alexander Mathis who also will begin an assistant professorship at [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|Swiss Federal Institute of Technology]] in the summer of 2020.<ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~amathis/|title=Alexander Mathis {{!}} About|website=www.people.fas.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mathis, Mackenzie Weygandt}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:University of Oregon alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American neuroscientist}}\n'''Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis''', is an American neuroscientist and principal investigator at the [[Rowland Institute for Science|Rowland Institute]] at [[Harvard University]]. Her lab investigates the neural basis of adaptive motor behaviors in mice to inform future translational research in neurological diseases. {{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Rowland Institute at Harvard University\n| alma_mater        = University of Oregon, Harvard University\n| known_for         = DeepLabCut deep learning software for animal pose estimation\n| awards            = Ernest Peralta Fund Award, Rowland Junior Fellowship, Women & the Brain (WATB) Fellowship for Advancement in Brain Science, CZI Essential Open Source Software for Science - grant for DeepLabCut, ELLIS Society Fellow, Natural Intelligence, Mind, Brain & Behavior Harvard University Faculty Award, eLife Travel Grant Award Winner, NVIDIA GPU Grant\n| Institutions      = Rowland Institute at Harvard University\n}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMathis conducted her undergraduate education at the [[University of Oregon]] receiving a bachelors of science in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/team|title=People|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> She then worked as a senior research technician and lab manager at the Project A.L.S. Laboratory for Stem Cell Research at [[Columbia University]] from 2007 to 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/team|title=People|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.harvard.edu/mwamoroso/home|title=Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis|website=scholar.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Working under the mentorship of Dr. Christopher E. Henderson and Dr. [[Hynek Wichterle]], Mathis modelled [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]] (A.L.S.) using [[stem cell]]-derived motor neurons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.harvard.edu/mwamoroso/home|title=Mackenzie Weygandt Mathis|website=scholar.harvard.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> During her time in the lab, she published a first author scientific paper in the [[The Journal of Neuroscience|Journal of Neuroscience]] which offered a novel protocol for generating human limb-innervating neural subtypes in vitro for use in neurological disease research.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Amoroso|first=Mackenzie W.|last2=Croft|first2=Gist F.|last3=Williams|first3=Damian J.|last4=O'Keeffe|first4=Sean|last5=Carrasco|first5=Monica A.|last6=Davis|first6=Anne R.|last7=Roybon|first7=Laurent|last8=Oakley|first8=Derek H.|last9=Maniatis|first9=Tom|last10=Henderson|first10=Christopher E.|last11=Wichterle|first11=Hynek|date=2013-01-09|title=Accelerated high-yield generation of limb-innervating motor neurons from human stem cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23303937|journal=The Journal of Neuroscience: The Official Journal of the Society for Neuroscience|volume=33|issue=2|pages=574\u2013586|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.0906-12.2013|issn=1529-2401|pmc=3711539|pmid=23303937}}</ref> Mathis then moved to Boston and joined the graduate program in molecular and cellular biology (MCB) at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On her way to completing her PhD, she also completed a master's degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/team|title=People|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> During her PhD, Mathis conducted research on the neural circuits underlying reward prediction errors under the mentorship of Dr. [[Naoshige Uchida]] at the Harvard Center for Brain Science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> In her first year as a graduate student, Mathis received an [[National Science Foundation|National Science Foundation Fellowship]] to fund her graduate research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/archive/four-mcb-graduate-students-receive-nsf-fellowships-in-2013/|title=FOUR MCB GRADUATE STUDENTS RECEIVE NSF FELLOWSHIPS IN 2013|date=2013-04-11|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Mathis was able to merge her interests in motor control with Uchida's expertise in large scale neural recordings and behavioral analysis to forge a new scientific direction in the lab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and publish a first author paper in [[Neuron (journal)|Neuron]] by the end of her PhD regarding the essential role played by the [[somatosensory cortex]] in forelimb [[motor adaptation]] in rodents.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mathis|first=Mackenzie Weygandt|last2=Mathis|first2=Alexander|last3=Uchida|first3=Naoshige|date=2017-03-22|title=Somatosensory Cortex Plays an Essential Role in Forelimb Motor Adaptation in Mice|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627317301575|journal=Neuron|language=en|volume=93|issue=6|pages=1493\u20131503.e6|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2017.02.049|issn=0896-6273}}</ref> Following her PhD, Mathis was awarded the Rowland Junior Fellowship which provided five years of funding to start her own lab at Harvard's Rowland Institute in Cambridge, MA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Prior to founding the Mathis Lab at Harvard, Mathis was awarded the [http://womenandthebrain.org/ Women & the Brain] (WATB) Fellowship for Advancement in Brain Science which provided her with the funding to bridge the gap between her PhD skills and her independent career goals through postdoctoral work in [[Germany]] under the mentorship of [[Matthias Bethge]]\u2019s at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> In her postdoctoral work, Mathis focused on pioneering [[deep learning]] tools for neural and behavioral analysis which served as a critical step towards her independent career.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mathis|first=Alexander|last2=Mamidanna|first2=Pranav|last3=Abe|first3=Taiga|last4=Cury|first4=Kevin M.|last5=Murthy|first5=Venkatesh N.|last6=Mathis|first6=Mackenzie W.|last7=Bethge|first7=Matthias|date=2018-04-09|title=Markerless tracking of user-defined features with deep learning|url=http://arxiv.org/abs/1804.03142|journal=arXiv:1804.03142 [cs, q-bio, stat]}}</ref>\n\n== Career and research ==\nIn 2017, Mathis started her lab at the [[Rowland Institute for Science|Rowland Institute]] at [[Harvard University]] with a goal of reverse engineering neural circuits that drive adaptive motor behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Through large-scale neural recordings and building novel robotic and machine learning tools, the [http://www.mousemotorlab.org/ Mathis Lab] probes neural circuits and analyzes behavioral outputs to better understand how brain function relates to behavior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brain.harvard.edu/?people=mackenzie-mathis|title=Mackenzie Mathis|website=Harvard Brain Science Initiative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Mathis is dedicated to the concept of [[open science]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologynetworks.com/neuroscience/articles/interview-a-deeper-cut-into-behavior-with-mackenzie-mathis-327618|title=Interview: A Deeper Cut Into Behavior With Mackenzie Mathis|website=Neuroscience from Technology Networks|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and as such, the novel [[deep learning]] tool she designed, in collaboration with Dr. Alexander Mathis, is [[open access]] such that researchers worldwide have access to the code in order to use this tool to analyze animal behaviors in an unbiased and precise way to inform a better understanding of how neural activity drives specific behaviors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologynetworks.com/neuroscience/articles/interview-a-deeper-cut-into-behavior-with-mackenzie-mathis-327618|title=Interview: A Deeper Cut Into Behavior With Mackenzie Mathis|website=Neuroscience from Technology Networks|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=c823ad30-6ec7-11ea-bf9b-c9cdf6e03cf3&url=L25ld3MvZmVhdHVyZXMvMjAxOS0wNi0xOC9hcHBsZS1nb29nbGUtYW5kLWZhY2Vib29rLWFyZS1yYWlkaW5nLWFuaW1hbC1yZXNlYXJjaC1sYWJz|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/deeplabcut-tracking-animal-movements/564338/|title=A Game-Changing AI Tool for Tracking Animal Movements|last=Yong|first=Ed|date=2018-07-03|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The deep learning tool designed by Mathis is called [http://www.mousemotorlab.org/deeplabcut DeepLabCut]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/deeplabcut|title=DeepLabCut|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> which relies on [[transfer learning]] to optimize an existing [[neural network]] to a desired dataset after sufficient training.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/deeplabcut-tracking-animal-movements/564338/|title=A Game-Changing AI Tool for Tracking Animal Movements|last=Yong|first=Ed|date=2018-07-03|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Mathis has shown the versatility of this tool on many diverse datasets highlighting the robust design and potential for wide use in fields even beyond neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2018/08/an-open-source-ai-tool-available-to-study-movement-across-behaviors-and-species/|title=An open-source AI tool available to study movement across behaviors and species|date=2018-08-30|website=Harvard Gazette|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Mathis announced that she would be moving to the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|Swiss Federal Institute of Technology]], working within the Brain Mind Institute & Center for Neuroprosthetics (<nowiki>http://www.mousemotorlab.org/#research</nowiki>) as a tenure-track professor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/|title=adaptive motor control lab|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evangelista|first=Sandy|date=2019-09-27|title=Nominations of EPFL professors|url=https://actu.epfl.ch/news/nominations-of-epfl-professors-135/|language=en}}</ref> The lab will be moving to [[Campus Biotech]] in [[Geneva|Geneva, Switzerland]] in the summer of 2020, where Mathis will hold the Bertarelli Foundation Chair of Integrative Neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/news|title=News|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evangelista|first=Sandy|date=2019-09-27|title=Nominations of EPFL professors|url=https://actu.epfl.ch/news/nominations-of-epfl-professors-135/|language=en}}</ref>\u00a0\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n\n* 2019 - 2020 CZI Essential Open Source Software for Science - grant for DeepLabCut<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chanzuckerberg.com/eoss/proposals/|title=CZI \u2013 Essential Open Source Software for Science|website=Chan Zuckerberg Initiative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n* 2019 ELLIS Society Fellow, Natural Intelligence<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/team|title=People|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n* 2018 Mind, Brain & Behavior Harvard University Faculty Award \n* 2018 eLife Travel Grant Award Winner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elifesciences.org/inside-elife/1b397041/early-career-researcher-travel-grants-2018-first-seven-authors-selected|title=Early-career researcher travel grants 2018: First seven authors selected|date=2018-04-03|website=eLife|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n* 2017 NVIDIA GPU Grant<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/news|title=News|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2017 - 2022 Rowland Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/education/mco-graduate-open-lab-rowland-institute-harvard/|title=MCO Graduate to Open Lab Through the Rowland Institute at Harvard|date=2017-03-14|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2017 Women & the Brain Fellowship for Advancement of Neuroscience<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bethgelab.org/home/funding/|title=BETHGE LAB \u00b7 Funding|website=bethgelab.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2013 - 2018 National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellowship Life Sciences \u2013 Neuroscience<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/archive/four-mcb-graduate-students-receive-nsf-fellowships-in-2013/|title=FOUR MCB GRADUATE STUDENTS RECEIVE NSF FELLOWSHIPS IN 2013|date=2013-04-11|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2013, \u201914, \u201916 Harvard University Certificate of Distinction in Teaching (MCB80, MCB145)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/tag/awards/|title=awards Archives|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2014 Dr. Ernest Peralta Fund Award for Best Qualifying Exam proposal & defense, Harvard<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/|title=adaptive motor control lab|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcb.harvard.edu/tag/ernest-peralta-fund-award/|title=Ernest Peralta Fund Award Archives|website=Harvard University - Department of Molecular & Cellular Biology|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* 2012 - 2013 Morris E. Zukerman Graduate Fellowship - awarded to top students in brain sciences at Harvard GSAS<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mousemotorlab.org/|title=adaptive motor control lab|website=adaptive motor control lab|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=IhqY9XgAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Mackenzie W. Mathis - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n* '''Mathis MW''', Mathis A, Uchida N. Somatosensory Cortex Plays an Essential Role in Forelimb Motor Adaptation in Mice, '''''Neuron.''''' 2017. 10.1016/j.neuron.2017.02.049. \n* Ho R, Sances S, Gowing G, '''Amoroso, MW''', et al. ALS disrupts spinal motor neuron maturation and aging pathways within gene co-expression networks. '''''Nature Neuroscience''','' 2016.\n* Li H, Kuwajima T, Oakley D, et al. Protein Prenylation Constitutes an Endogenous Brake on Axonal Growth. '''''Cell Reports'''''. 2016.16 (2) :545 - 558. \n* Cohen JY, '''Amoroso MW''', Uchida N. Serotonergic neurons signal reward and punishment on multiple timescales. '''''eLife'''''. 2015. 10.7554/eLife.06346\n* Re D B, Le Verche V, Yu C, '''Amoroso, MW''', \u00a0et al. Necroptosis Drives Motor Neuron Death in Models of Both Sporadic and Familial ALS. '''''Neuron'''''. 2014. 81 :1001 - 1008. \n* '''Amoroso MW''', Croft GF, Williams DJ, et al. Accelerated High-Yield Generation of Limb-Innervating Motor Neurons from Human Stem Cells. '''''Journal of Neuroscience.''''' 2013. 33 (2) :574 - 586.\n* N\u00e9delec S, Peljto M, Shi P, et al. Concentration-Dependent Requirement for Local Protein Synthesis in Motor Neuron Subtype-Specific Response to Axon Guidance Cues. '''''Journal of Neuroscience''''', 2012. 32 (4) :1496 - 1506. \n* Takazawa T, Croft GF, '''Amoroso MW''', et al. Maturation of Spinal Motor Neurons Derived from Human Embryonic Stem Cells. '''''PLOS ONE''''', 2012. 7 (7) :e40154. \n* Boulting GL*, Kiskinis E*, Croft GF*, '''Amoroso, MW*''', Oakley, D* et al. A functionally characterized test set of human induced pluripotent stem cells. '''''Nature Biotechnology''''', 2011. 29 (3) :279 - 286. \n* Bock C, Kiskinis E, Verstappen G, et al. Reference Maps of human ES and iPS cell variation enable high-throughput characterization of pluripotent cell lines. '''''Cell''''', 2011.144 (3) :439 - 452.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMathis is currently married to neuroscientist Dr. Alexander Mathis who also will begin an assistant professorship at [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|Swiss Federal Institute of Technology]] in the summer of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/deeplabcut-tracking-animal-movements/564338/|title=A Game-Changing AI Tool for Tracking Animal Movements|last=Yong|first=Ed|date=2018-07-03|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~amathis/|title=Alexander Mathis {{!}} About|website=www.people.fas.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mathis, Mackenzie Weygandt}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:University of Oregon alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Blythwood", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 0 bare reference(s) with reFill 2\u2013deduplicated citations and category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mackenzie_Weygandt_Mathis"}
{"title_page": "Beauty and the Beast (1991 soundtrack)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Beauty and the Beast: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      = Beautyandthebeastsoundtrack.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 24, 1991 <small>(1991 Original release)</small><br />December 18, 2001 <small>(2001 Special Edition reissue)</small><br />September 14, 2010 <small>(2010 re-release)</small><br />February 9, 2018 <small>(2018 Legacy Collection re-release)</small>\n| recorded   = 1990\u20131991\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[film score]]\n| length     = 50:12 <small>(1991 Original Release)</small><br />1:04:43 <small>(2001 Special Edition Reissue)</small><br />53:26 <small>(2010 Re-release)</small>\n| label      = [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n| producer   = [[Howard Ashman]]<br />[[Alan Menken]]<br />[[Walter Afanasieff]]<br />[[Robert Louis Buchanan|Robert Buchanan]]\n| chronology = [[Walt Disney Records discography|Walt Disney Animation Studios]]\n| prev_title = [[The Rescuers Down Under#Music|The Rescuers Down Under]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Aladdin (1992 soundtrack)|Aladdin]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = 2001 Special Edition\n | type    = Soundtrack\n | cover   = Beautybeastspecialeditionostbox.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Front jacket\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = 2001 Special Edition.\n | type    = Soundtrack\n | cover   = Beautybeastspecialeditionostcover.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Front of the booklet of the 2001 Special Edition.\n}}{{Singles\n | name        = Beauty and the Beast: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Beauty and the Beast (Disney song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\n | single1date = November 25, 1991\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Beauty and the Beast: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack''''' is the official [[soundtrack album]] to the 1991 [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Disney]] animated feature film, ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]''. Originally released on October 24, 1991, by [[Walt Disney Records]], the album's first half \u2013 tracks 2 to 9 \u2013 generally contains the film's [[Number (music)|musical number]]<nowiki/>s, all of which were written by composer [[Alan Menken]] and lyricist [[Howard Ashman]], while its latter half \u2013 tracks 10 to 14 \u2013 features its <nowiki/>[[Film score|musical score]], composed solely by Menken. While the majority of the album's content remains within the [[musical theatre]] genre, its songs have also been influenced by [[Music of France|French]], [[Classical music|classical]], [[pop music|pop]] and [[Broadway musical|Broadway music]]. Credited to Various Artists, ''Beauty and the Beast: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'' features performances by the film's main cast \u2013 [[Paige O'Hara]], [[Richard White (actor)|Richard White]], [[Jesse Corti]], [[Jerry Orbach]], [[Angela Lansbury]] and [[Robby Benson]] \u2013 in order of appearance. Additionally, the album features recording artists [[Celine Dion]] and [[Peabo Bryson]], who perform a pop rendition of the film's [[theme song|title and theme song]], \"Beauty and the Beast\", which simultaneously serves as the soundtrack's only single.\n\nFollowing a difficult period during where [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Feature Animation]] struggled to release successful animated feature films, the studio, inspired by their most recent animated success ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]] ''(1989), decided to adapt the fairy tale \"[[Beauty and the Beast]]\" into an [[Musical film|animated musical film]] after a non-musical adaptation had been attempted that failed to impress [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], the chairman of Walt Disney Studios. Katzenberg ordered that production on the film be started over from scratch, hiring songwriting team Howard Ashman and Alan Menken, who had just recently completed scoring ''The Little Mermaid'', to write the film's songs. Dion and Bryson were hired to record a pop version of \u2013 and draw media attention to \u2013 the film's title song. Ashman, who was initially hesitant to join the project, died of [[AIDS]] before the film's completion and the album's release.\n\nMuch like ''Beauty and the Beast'', the soundtrack was a massive critical success, receiving universal praise and recognition from both film and music critics. The music featured on the album won several awards, including the [[49th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], the [[64th Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Score]] and the [[35th Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]] for [[Best Instrumental Composition Written for a Motion Picture or for Television]]. Its title track and only single, \"[[Beauty and the Beast (Disney song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\", achieved similar success, winning the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] and Grammy Awards for both [[Best song written for visual media|Best Song Written for Visual Media]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals]]. The soundtrack was also nominated for a Grammy Award for Album of the Year.\n\nIn December 2001, the soundtrack was re-released as a ''Special Edition'' to coincide with the [[IMAX]] re-issue of the film and the upcoming two-disc [[Walt Disney Platinum and Diamond Editions#Soundtracks|Platinum Edition]]. The new release featured the film version of \"Transformation\", which had been replaced with an early unused version in some early pressings, the newly animated song \"Human Again\", the original instrumental intended for the \"Transformation\" scene, (titled \"Death of the Beast (Early Version)\" here) and demos for \"Be Our Guest\" and the title track. In September 2010, the soundtrack was re-released again as a [[Walt Disney Platinum and Diamond Editions#Music releases|Diamond Edition]] soundtrack, to coincide with the successful Blu-ray and DVD Diamond Edition release of the film, the 1991 version of the soundtrack was released and included [[Jordin Sparks]]' cover of \"Beauty and the Beast\" as a bonus track. The soundtrack was [[reissue|reissued]] as the fourteenth entry in ''[[Walt Disney Records the Legacy Collection|The Legacy Collection]]'' on February 9, 2018 and includes previously unreleased score.\n\n==Background==\nDuring the 1970s and 1980s, [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Feature Animation]] struggled to release animated feature films that achieved the levels of success of some of the studio's earlier productions did. In 1989, [[Walt Disney Pictures]] released ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]. ''An [[Musical film|animated musical]] that features songs written by lyricist [[Howard Ashman]] and composer [[Alan Menken]], ''The Little Mermaid'' was both a tremendous critical and commercial success. Hoping to release a film that achieved similar success, the studio decided to adapt the fairy tale \"[[Beauty and the Beast]]\" by [[Jeanne-Marie Le Prince de Beaumont]] into an animated film.\n\nPrior to getting professionally involved with Disney, Ashman and Menken had collaborated on a [[Little Shop of Horrors (1960 film)|musical adaptation]] of ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'' and its subsequent musical [[Little Shop of Horrors (film)|film adaptation]]. Following the studio's attempt to adapt the fairy tale into a non-musical animated film under the direction of Richard Purdum, Disney CEO [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], dissatisfied by the direction in which the film was headed, ordered that it be scrapped and restarted from scratch, this time in the form of a musical. In addition to hiring a screenwriter, Katzenberg recruited Ashman and Menken to write the film's songs.\n\n===Ashman's health===\nAshman was initially reluctant to agree to work on ''Beauty and the Beast'' because he had just recently been diagnosed with [[AIDS]]. Additionally, he had already begun writing songs for ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]] ''(1992). Ashman's health began deteriorating soon after he completed ''The Little Mermaid''. However, he wanted his illness to remain secret and decided to tell few about it. Too weak to travel, Ashman requested that he be allowed to work on the film's songs from his home, causing Menken and the filmmakers to frequently travel from the film's studio in [[Burbank, California]] to his home in New York in order to collaborate with him. Ashman wrote the majority of the song's lyrics from his deathbed.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/beauty-and-the-plague|title = Beauty and the Plague|website = Vice|publisher = Vice|accessdate = 18 September 2013|last = Sunderland|first = Mitchell}}</ref><ref>https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-gay-lefou-howard-ashman</ref><ref>https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/16583/don-Hahn-interview-beauty-and-the-beast-howard-Ashman-the-lion-king-south-park-and-frankenweenie</ref>\n\n==Content and composition==\nLyricist Howard Ashman and composer Alan Menken intended for the songs in ''Beauty and the Beast'' to serve as [[plot device]]s and assist in the telling of its story. According to Menken, the film's songs grew out of the fact that the film was written to \"almost ... exist as a stage musical.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://movies.about.com/od/rapunzel/a/Alan-Menken-Interview.htm|title = Exclusive Interview with Alan Menken on 'Tangled'|website = About.com|last = Murray|first = Rebecca|publisher = About.com|accessdate = 17 September 2013|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110120180232/http://movies.about.com/od/rapunzel/a/Alan-Menken-Interview.htm|archive-date = 20 January 2011|url-status = dead}}</ref> Stylistically, Ashman and Menken drew creative influence from several musical styles and genres, including [[French classical music|French]], [[Classical music|classical]] and [[Broadway musical|Broadway music]], using them as reference and inspiration when composing the film's songs.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.comicmix.com/news/2010/10/02/alan-menken-revisits-beauty-and-the-beast/|title = Alan Menken Revisits \u2018beauty & The Beast\u2019|date = October 2, 2010|accessdate = 18 September 2013|website = Comic Mix|publisher = Comic Mix|last = Greenberger|first = Robert}}</ref> Menken also revealed that the film's songs and score tend to convey a wide variety of emotions, ranging from poignancy to humor and joy.<ref name=\"Interview with Beauty\">{{Cite web|url = http://staticmultimedia.com/blu-ray-dvd/interview-with-beauty-and-the-beast-composer-alan-menken|title = Interview with Beauty and the Beast Composer Alan Menken|website = Static Multimedia|publisher = Static Multimedia|date = October 4, 2010|accessdate = 17 September 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053401/http://staticmultimedia.com/blu-ray-dvd/interview-with-beauty-and-the-beast-composer-alan-menken|archivedate = 21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhile composing the orchestral score that accompanies the film's [[prologue]], Menken was inspired by the French [[Suite (music)|suite]] ''[[The Carnival of the Animals]]'' by [[Camille Saint-Sa\u00ebns]], referring to it as his own version of Saint-Sa\u00ebns' composition.<ref name=\":2\" /> Menken believes that all properly structured musicals should feature an \"I Want\" song because they are essentially \"about a character having a big dream, then [there's] some obstacle to that quest.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url = http://insidemovies.ew.com/2010/11/24/alan-menken-tangled/|title = Alan Menken discusses 'Tangled' and the past, present, and future of the animated musical|website = Entertainment Weekly|publisher = Entertainment Weekly Inc|date = November 24, 2010|accessdate = 17 September 2013|last = Blauvelt|first = Christian}}\n</ref> \"[[Belle (Beauty and the Beast song)|Belle]]\", the film's opening number, is an \"orchestra-driven\",<ref name=\":15\" /> \"snare-tapping\" song. Accompanied by a full orchestra,<ref name=\":14\" /> it is considered ''Beauty and the Beast''<nowiki/>'s \"I Want\" song.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-11-24/film/tangled-looks-and-feels-great-so-why-is-disney-selling-it-short/|title = Tangled Looks and Feels Great, So Why Is Disney Selling It Short?|date = November 24, 2010|accessdate = 17 September 2013|website = The Village Voice|publisher = Village Voice, LLC|last = Kois|first = Dan}}</ref> Musically, Menken based \"Belle\" on the narrative style of a traditional [[operetta]], describing it as \"something to portray [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]] in a world that is so protected and safe.\" Menken described the film's following musical number, \"[[Gaston (Disney song)|Gaston]]\", as a hilarious \"drinking song sung by basically a group of [[Neanderthal]] level guys in praise of a complete lug-head\", referring to Ashman's choice of song lyrics as humorous and \"[[Tongue-in-cheek|tongue in cheek]]\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWhen it came time to write the film's large-scale \"scintillating\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.allmusic.com/composition/beauty-and-the-beast-film-score-mc0002386769|title = Alan Menken Beauty and the Beast, film score|accessdate = 18 September 2013|website = AllMusic|publisher = All Media Network, LLC|last = Dickey|first = Timothy}}</ref> musical number \"[[Be Our Guest]]\",  Menken originally composed and provided Ashman with a simple melody that was initially intended for temporary use only, simply for the purpose of allowing his co-writer to start developing the song's lyrics. He labeled the rough composition \"the dummy\". However, Menken eventually gave up on his attempt to improve upon the song's simple melody, and it ultimately became the version to which Ashman wrote his lyrics.<ref name=\":2\" /> Menken described \"Be Our Guest\" as a song that is both \"simple and tuneful\" that \"let[s] the lyric shine.\"<ref name=\"Q&A: Composer Alan Menken\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.theartsdesk.com/theatre/theartsdesk-qa-composer-alan-menken|title = theartsdesk Q&A: Composer Alan Menken|accessdate = 18 September 2013|date = May 16, 2010|website = The Arts Desk|publisher = The Arts Desk Ltd|last = Rees|first = Jasper}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, Ashman and Menken had written a rather lengthy, large-scale musical number for the film called \"Human Again\". However, when it was deemed \"too ambitious\", they swiftly wrote and replaced it with a smaller-scale musical number entitled \"Something There\".<ref name=\":2\" /> According to Menken, the film's [[Theme song|theme and title song]], \"[[Beauty and the Beast (Disney song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\", was \"a very hard song to come by\" despite its relative simplicity.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"Q&A: Composer Alan Menken\"/> He revealed that the writing process for \"Beauty and the Beast\" was the longest period of time that he had ever devoted to one particular song. Written to resemble a [[lullaby]], Ashman and Menken conceived \"Beauty and the Beast\" as \"a song that could have a life outside the movie.\" The film's final musical number, \"The Mob Song\", was written as what Menken described as \"a macho adventure underscore\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Single===\nWhen the film was released, it garnered three separate [[64th Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Belle (Disney song)|Belle]]\", \"[[Be Our Guest]]\" and \"[[Beauty and the Beast (Disney song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\". Producer [[Don Hahn]] expressed concern that this would cause confusion among audiences and voters, and potentially result in an unfavorable tie. In order to prevent this from happening, the studio fought in favor of the film's title song and decided to release a [[pop music|pop]] <nowiki/>rendition of \"[[Beauty and the Beast (Disney song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\" as a commercial single in an attempt to persuade voters to vote for it.<ref name=\"how 'Beauty and the Beast' changed animation\">{{Cite web|url = http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/02/22/oscars-1992-beauty-and-the-beast/|title = Oscars 1992: Producer Don Hahn on how 'Beauty and the Beast' changed animation|last = Young|first = John|website = Entertainment Weekly|publisher = Entertainment Weekly Inc|date = February 22, 2012|accessdate = 17 September 2013}}</ref> When \"Beauty and the Beast\" was written, it was composed with the potential of having \"half a life outside the movie.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Menken revealed that this was the first time one of his compositions had been rearranged and \"turned into ear candy\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.ibatom.com/atthemovies/25285781/detail.html|title = Menken Still Enchanted By Beauty Of 'Beast'|date = October 5, 2010|website = Internet Broadcasting|accessdate = 17 September 2013|publisher = Internet Broadcasting|last = Lammers|first = Tim}}</ref>\n\nMenken recruited musician [[Robbie Buchanan]] to arrange<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.discogs.com/Alan-Menken-Howard-Ashman-Beauty-And-The-Beast-Original-Motion-Picture-Soundtrack-Special-Edition/release/4702387|title = Alan Menken, Howard Ashman \u2013 Beauty And The Beast (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) (Special Edition)|accessdate = 18 September 2013|website = Discogs|publisher = Discogs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/robbie-buchanan-mn0000831070/credits|title = Robbie Buchanan|accessdate = 18 September 2013|website = Allmusic|publisher = All Media Network, LLC}}</ref> \"Beauty and the Beast\" into the form of a pop duet<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://collider.com/entertainment/interviews/article.asp/aid/6139/tcid/1|title = Stephen Schwartz and Alan Menken Interview \u2013 ENCHANTED|date = November 21, 2007|website = Collider|publisher = Collider.com|accessdate = 17 September 2013}}</ref> while [[Walter Afanasieff]] was responsible for producing the track.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/walter-afanasieff-mn0000380606/biography|title = Walter Afanasieff|accessdate = 17 September 2013|website = Allmusic|publisher = All Media Network, LLC|last = Hogan|first = Ed}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://web.poptower.com/walter-afanasieff.htm|title = Walter Afanasieff|website = Pop Tower|publisher = Pop Tower|accessdate = 17 September 2013}}</ref> Afanasieff also assisted Buchanan in the arranging of the song.<ref name=\"Walter Afanasieff\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.walterafanasieff.com/motionpictures.html|title = Motion Pictures|website = Walter Afanasieff|accessdate = 17 September 2013|publisher = Walter Afanasieff}}</ref> Menken was ultimately pleased with Afanasieff's production, explaining, \"Walter Afanasieff ... took it and really molded it into something very different than I ever intended and I grew to love it. In a way, Walter made it his own, and I love that.\"<ref name=\":5\" /> Because Disney could not afford to hire a \"big singer\", they drafted Canadian singer [[Celine Dion]], who was relatively new to the music industry at the time, to record \"[[Beauty and the Beast (Disney song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\". However, the studio feared that she would not draw much media attention because of her relative obscurity in the United States, so they hired American singer [[Peabo Bryson]], who was a more well-known recording artist at the time, to perform alongside her.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"how 'Beauty and the Beast' changed animation\"/> The newly arranged song was released as the album's lead single on November 25, 1991.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.celinedion.com/ca/node/151258|title = Beauty and the Beast|date = December 10, 2010|author = Carlos|website = Celine Dion|accessdate = 17 September 2013|publisher = Sony Music Entertainment Canada Inc|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054820/http://www.celinedion.com/ca/node/151258|archive-date = 21 September 2013|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic |class=album|id=beauty-and-the-beast-mw0000042616|pure_url=yes}}|title=Beauty and the Beast - Disney, Alan Menken |first=Tavia|last=Hobart|work=Allmusic|publisher=All Media Network, LLC|accessdate=2010-05-29}}</ref>\n|rev2 = Filmtracks\n|rev2score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>[http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/beauty_beast.html]</ref>\n|rev3 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n|rev3Score = 4.5/5<ref>[https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/42895/Disney-Soundtracks-Beauty-and-the-Beast/]</ref>\n}}\nSimilar to the overwhelmingly positive critical response that the film received, ''Beauty and the Beast: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack ''was met with universal acclaim from both music and film critics, garnering nearly unanimous praise for both its songs and score. Tavia Hobart of [[AllMusic]] awarded the soundtrack a nearly perfect overall score of 4.5/5 stars, describing Ashman and Menken's compositions as \"positively delightful.\" However, she felt that the album's orchestral score was not as good as ''[[The Little Mermaid (soundtrack)|The Little Mermaid]]''<nowiki/>. [[Filmtracks.com|Filmtracks]] <nowiki/>was very enthusiastic about the album, praising each of its songs and labeling them \"remarkably upbeat\". The reviewer also praised Ashman and Menken for avoiding \"stupid comedic performances to appeal to children.\" Unlike AllMusic's opinion, the reviewer felt that the score was \"a vast improvement\" over ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/>'s. [[Sputnikmusic|Sputnikmusik]]'s Irving Tan awarded the album a \"superb\" overall rating of 4.5/5. Praising the film's entire collection of songs in a detailed review, Tan accredited the overall appeal of the soundtrack with much the film's success.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/42895/Disney-Soundtracks-Beauty-and-the-Beast/|title = Disney Soundtracks - Beauty and the Beast|date = April 10, 2011|website = Sputnikmusic|publisher = IndieClick Music Network|last = Tan|first = Irving|accessdate = 18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' was released in October  1991, several film and entertainment critics awarded specific praise to its music, both songs and score. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<nowiki/>'s [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] wrote, \"The songs unleash a chemical reaction of happiness.\"<ref name=\"EW:14\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20483133_20556652,00.html|title = Beauty and the Beast 3D (2012)|date = January 12, 2012|last = Schwarzbaum|first = Lisa|publisher = Entertainment Weekly Inc|website = Entertainment Weekly|accessdate = 18 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nJust as the film made history by becoming the first animated film to receive a Best Picture Oscar nomination, so too the soundtrack made history by becoming the first animated film soundtrack to receive an Album of the Year Grammy nomination (to date, no other animated film soundtrack has been nominated in this category). The pop version of the title track \"Beauty and the Beast\" also received Grammy nominations for Record of the Year and Song of the Year. In total, the soundtrack won 3 Grammys for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance (Celine Dion & John Greenhalgh, Best Pop Instrumental Performance (Richard Kauffman), and Best Song Written for a Motion Picture (Alan Menken).<ref>[http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1993/grammys.htm]</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nIn the movie track eight comes after track nine.