r-to-guaido-meeting-with-professionals-and-technicians-nAgepMyp|title=Streaming services disrupted in Venezuela prior to Guaid\u00f3 meeting with professionals and technicians|date=16 May 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=19 May 2019}}</ref> He discussed the mediations in Norway, the release of [[Iv\u00e1n Simonovis]] and the discussions with the [[United States Southern Command|US Southern Command]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/guaido-reunion-en-noruega-es-una-iniciativa-mas/|title=Juan Guaid\u00f3: \"Reuni\u00f3n en Noruega es una iniciativa m\u00e1s\"|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Gabriela|date=16 May 2019|website=El Pitazo|access-date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|18\n|Guaid\u00f3's speech from [[Guatire]]<ref name=netblocks18May>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/youtube-and-online-services-restricted-in-venezuela-as-guaido-speaks-from-guatire-zA4zDlyR|title=YouTube and online services restricted in Venezuela as Guaido speaks from Guatire|date=18 May 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|21\n|National Assembly session on the gasoline shortage crisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/youtube-and-periscope-disrupted-in-venezuela-during-national-assembly-live-stream-JBQxZbAo|title=YouTube and Periscope disrupted in Venezuela during National Assembly live stream|date=21 May 2019|website=NetBlocks|language=en-US|access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|23\n|Partial coverage of Guaido's speeches, offering medicine and aid at the Convent of the Agustinas in [[Los Teques]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/youtube-and-online-services-restricted-in-venezuela-as-guaido-tours-los-teques-miranda-QAd2qPyl|title=YouTube and online services restricted in Venezuela as Guaid\u00f3 tours Los Teques, Miranda|date=23 May 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|24\n|Guaid\u00f3's national plan discussion from [[Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/streaming-services-restricted-in-venezuela-as-guaido-discusses-national-plan-from-andres-bello-catholic-university-PyXR1zAE|title=Streaming services restricted in Venezuela as Guaid\u00f3 discusses national plan from Andr\u00e9s Bello Catholic University|access-date=25 May 2019|date=24 May 2019|website=NetBlocks}}</ref>\n|-\n|26\n|Guaid\u00f3 speaks to his supporters in [[Barquisimeto]], [[Lara (state)|Lara]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lapatilla.com/2019/05/26/netblocks-reporta-bloqueo-de-periscope-durante-alocucion-de-guaido-26may/|title=NetBlocks reports Periscope blockade during address of Guaid\u00f3 # 26May|date=26 May 2019|work=[[La Patilla]]|access-date=29 May 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n|-\n|28\n|National Assembly session<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/ong-alerta-sobre-bloqueo-de-cantv-a-youtube-para-evitar-difusion-de-mensaje-de-guaido/|title=ONG denuncia bloqueo de Cantv a Youtube para evitar difusi\u00f3n de mensaje de Guaid\u00f3|date=28 May 2019|website=El Pitazo|language=es|access-date=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |June\n|11\n|National Assembly session<ref name=\"netblokcs17june\">{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/streaming-services-restricted-in-venezuela-as-guaido-holds-press-conference-in-caracas-xyMGQGAZ|title=Streaming services restricted in Venezuela as Guaid\u00f3 holds press conference in Caracas|date=17 June 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|15\n|Guaid\u00f3 speech in M\u00e9rida<ref name=\"netblokcs17june\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/06/15/netblocks-confirma-bloqueo-de-google-instagram-y-youtube-durante-discurso-de-guaido-en-merida-15jun/|title=Netblocks confirma bloqueo de Google, Instagram y YouTube durante discurso de Guaid\u00f3 en M\u00e9rida|date=15 June 2019|website=La Patilla|language=es|access-date=16 June 2019}}</ref> calling for investigations on his appointees in Colombia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/16/venezuelas-guaido-calls-for-probe-into-funds-for-military-defectors|title=Venezuela's Guaido calls for probe into funds for military defectors|date=16 June 2019|website=Euronews|access-date=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|17\n|Guaid\u00f3 international press conference in Caracas, discussing alleged charges on his appointees in Colombia<ref name=\"netblokcs17june\" />\n|-\n|18\n|National Assembly session, topics include the release and return of [[Gilber Caro]] and alleged charges on appointees in Colombia<ref name=netblocks18June>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/twitter-and-instagram-restricted-in-venezuela-during-national-assembly-session-XB7wk1B7|title=Twitter and Instagram restricted in Venezuela during National Assembly session|date=18 June 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|19\n|Guaid\u00f3 speech on food security and agriculture<ref name=\"netblocks18June\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |July\n|2\n|National Assembly session on navy captain [[Rafael Acosta Ar\u00e9valo]], who was detained and tortured to death<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/07/02/netblocks-confirma-bloqueo-de-youtube-bing-y-google-durante-sesion-de-la-an-2jul/|title=NetBlocks confirma bloqueo de YouTube, Bing y Google durante sesi\u00f3n de la AN #2Jul|date=2 July 2019|website=La Patilla|language=es|access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|5\n|Guaido's [[Independence Day (Venezuela)|Independence Day]] speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/tecnologia/venezuela-regimen-nicolas-maduro-bloqueo-youtube-google-bing-discurso-juan-guaido_0_TYJZ-uUOb.html|title=Venezuela: el r\u00e9gimen de Nicol\u00e1s Maduro bloque\u00f3 YouTube, Google y Bing durante el discurso de Juan Guaid\u00f3|date=5 July 2019|website=Clar\u00edn|language=es|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|November\n|16\n|Return of new summon of protests. Twitter, Facebook and YouTube restricted, mainly during Guaid\u00f3 speech<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/twitter-facebook-and-instagram-restricted-in-venezuela-on-day-of-planned-protests-98aMZv8o|title=Twitter, Facebook and Instagram restricted in Venezuela on day of planned protests|date=16 November 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|January\n|5\n|[[2020 Venezuelan National Assembly Delegated Committee election]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/la-humanidad/netblocks-confirma-bloqueo-de-twitter-youtube-instagram-y-facebook-por-parte-de-cantv-5ene/|title=Netblocks confirma bloqueo de Twitter, Youtube, Instagram y Facebook por parte de Cantv|last=Rodr\u00edguez|first=Ronny|date=5 January 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|access-date=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n\n== Phishing ==\nThe website \"Voluntarios X Venezuela\" was promoted by Guaid\u00f3 and the National Assembly to gather volunteers for humanitarian aid;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://talcualdigital.com/index.php/2019/02/16/personas-inscritas-en-voluntariosxvenezuela-comienzan-a-congregarse-para-acto-del-16f/|title=Sector salud y ciudadan\u00eda se congregan en actividad de VoluntariosxVenezuela el #16F|date=16 February 2019|work=Tal Cual Digital|accessdate=16 February 2019|language=es}}</ref> as of 16 February, Guaid\u00f3 said 600,000&nbsp;people had signed up.<ref name=\"Inscribieron\">{{cite news|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/mas-600000-personas-inscribieron-voluntariosxvenezuela_271121|title=M\u00e1s de 600.000 personas se inscribieron en VoluntariosxVenezuela|date=16 February 2019|work=El Nacional|accessdate=16 February 2019|language=es}}</ref> Between 12 and 13 February, CANTV users that tried to access were redirected to a mirror site with a different [[URL]] address. The mirror site asked for personal information: names, ID, address and telephone numbers. The fake site also hosted other [[phishing]] websites with the aim of obtaining email addresses, usernames and passwords. All the phishing websites used the [[.ve]] domain controlled by Conatel. This manipulation was denounced as a technique to identify dissidents to the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/d3mdxm/venezuela-government-hack-activists-phishing|title=Venezuela\u2019s Government Appears To Be Trying to Hack Activists With Phishing Pages|author=Franceschi-Bicchierai, Lorenzo and Jason Koebler|date=15 February 2019|website=Motherboard|access-date=15 February 2019}}<br />* {{Cite web|url=https://securelist.com/dns-manipulation-in-venezuela/89592/|title=DNS Manipulation in Venezuela in regards to the Humanitarian Aid Campaign|website=securelist.com|access-date=15 February 2019}}<br />* {{Cite news|url=http://www.ntn24.com/america-latina/venezuela/cantv-redirecciona-pagina-de-voluntarios-x-venezuela-portal-falso-103954|title=Cantv redirecciona p\u00e1gina de Voluntarios X Venezuela a portal falso|date=13 February 2019|access-date=15 February 2019|language=es|website=NTN24 {{!}} www.ntn24.com}}<br />* {{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/denuncian-creacion-sitio-web-identico-portal-voluntarios-venezuela_270938|title=Denuncian creaci\u00f3n un sitio web id\u00e9ntico al portal Voluntarios X Venezuela|date=15 February 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref> Following the phishing incident, the official site was completely blocked for CANTV users on 16 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/venezuela-humanitarian-aid-platform-blocked-GnAgJk8p|title=Venezuela humanitarian aid volunteer platform blocked|date=17 February 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Aggression, arrests and releases of press personnel ==\nThe Venezuelan press workers union denounced that in 2019, 40&nbsp;journalists had been illegally detained as of 12 March; the National Assembly Parliamentary Commission for Media declared that there had been 173&nbsp;aggressions against press workers as of 13 March. The commission planned to report these aggressions to the [[International Criminal Court]].<ref name=\"Escalona\"/>\n\nA delegation led by Michelle Bachelet, [[High Commissioner for Human Rights|United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] visited Venezuela on March. In a preliminary oral report, Bachelet denounced the escalating freedom of speech and press restrictions in Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=24374&LangID=E|title=Oral update on the situation of human rights in the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela|date=20 March 2019|publisher=OHCHR|accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[Efecto Cocuyo]]'' director, [[Luz Mely Reyes]], \"journalism is becoming 'very complicated' in Venezuela where power outages, patchy internet and threats of violence have made reporting increasingly difficult\".<ref name=france24reyes>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190418-journalism-venezuela-it-would-be-crime-stop|title=Journalism in Venezuela: it would be 'a crime' to stop|date=18 April 2019|website=France 24|access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref> Reyes told [[Agence France-Presse]] (AFP) in April that she is unsure that independent outlets like ''Efecto Cocuyo'' may \"survive\" in this economic and political situation.<ref name=france24reyes />\n\n=== January 2019 ===\nTwo journalists\u2014Beatriz Adri\u00e1n of [[Caracol Televisi\u00f3n]] and Osmary Hern\u00e1ndez of [[CNN]]\u2014were detained while on-air and covering the 13 January detention of Guaid\u00f3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/actualidad/venezuela-dos-periodistas-son-detenidas-plena-transmision-vivo-sebin-noticia-597051|title=Venezuela: Periodistas son detenidas en plena transmisi\u00f3n en vivo por el Sebin [Video]|date=13 January 2019|website=[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]]|language=es|access-date=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nBetween 29 and 30 January, at least eleven press personnel were arrested.<ref name=11trabajadores>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/01/31/regimen-de-maduro-ha-detenido-a-11-trabajadores-de-la-prensa-en-las-ultimas-24-horas/|title=R\u00e9gimen de Maduro ha detenido a 11 trabajadores de la prensa en las \u00faltimas 24 horas|date=31 January 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref> On the evening of 29 January, four journalists were arrested by the Maduro government while reporting near the Miraflores presidential palace\u2014Venezuelan journalists Ana Rodr\u00edguez of [[VPItv|VPI TV]] and Maiker Yriarte of [[TV Venezuela]], and Chilean journalists Rodrigo P\u00e9rez and Gonzalo Barahona of [[Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile|TVN Chile]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/01/29/periodistas-maikel-yriarte-y-ana-rodriguez-se-encuentran-detenidos-dentro-de-miraflores-denuncia-sntp/|title=Sntp denuncia detenci\u00f3n arbitraria de periodistas de TVVenezuela, VPI TV y TVN Chile|date=29 January 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=30 January 2019}}</ref> The two Venezuelan journalists were released; the Chilean journalists were deported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.t13.cl/noticia/nacional/mundo/periodistas-chilenos-fueron-deportados-desde-venezuela|title=Periodistas chilenos fueron deportados desde Venezuela|date=30 January 2019|website=Tele 13|language=es|access-date=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo French journalists from French TV show, ''[[Quotidien]]'', and their Venezuelan producer were detained for two days at [[El Helicoide]] on 30 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/01/30/sntp-denuncia-que-dos-periodistas-franceses-y-otro-venezolano-tambien-estan-detenidos-en-miraflores/|title=Sntp denuncia que dos periodistas franceses y otro venezolano tambi\u00e9n est\u00e1n detenidos en Miraflores|date=30 January 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=30 January 2019}}<br />* {{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/international/article/2019/01/30/venezuela-deux-journalistes-francais-de-l-emission-quotidien-sur-tmc-ont-ete-arretes_5416881_3210.html|title=Au Venezuela, la presse \u00e9trang\u00e8re dans le collimateur|date=30 January 2019|work=Le Monde|access-date=31 January 2019|language=fr}}<br />* {{cite web|url=https://www.20minutes.fr/arts-stars/medias/2444047-20190205-deux-journalistes-quotidien-racontent-detention-venezuela|title=Les deux journalistes de \"Quotidien\" racontent leur d\u00e9tention au Venezuela|website=20minutes.fr|language=fr|access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref> Three press workers of [[EFE]] were also arrested by SEBIN and [[Direcci\u00f3n General de Contrainteligencia Militar|DGCIM]]\u2014a Colombian photographer, a Colombian companion, and a Spanish companion.<ref name=11trabajadores />\n\n[[Jorge Arreaza]], Venezuelan Minister for Foreign Affairs, defended the detentions, stating that press workers were part \"of the media operation against the country\" that wanted \"to create a media scandal\" by not \"complying with the minimum prerequisites required by Venezuelan law\". Press organizations stated that they complied with the migration laws of Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/01/31/arreaza-denuncia-operacion-mediatica-tras-detencion-de-periodistas-extranjeros/|title=Arreaza denuncia \"operaci\u00f3n medi\u00e1tica\" tras detenci\u00f3n de periodistas extranjeros|date=31 January 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref> Maduro denied that journalists were detained by authorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/02/02/maduro-niega-detencion-de-periodistas-y-asegura-que-son-montajes-en-entrevista-con-jordi-evole-video/|title=Maduro niega detenci\u00f3n de periodistas y asegura que son \"montajes\" en entrevista con Jordi \u00c9vole (VIDEO)|date=2 February 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== February 2019 ===\n[[File:NASA Univision Hispanic Education Campaign DVIDS858679 (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Univision]] anchor [[Jorge Ramos (news anchor)|Jorge Ramos]] was detained by the Maduro administration in February 2019 after a live interview.]]\nDuring 23 February clashes, there were numerous reports of Venezuelan authorities and paramilitaries attacking press workers, including workers of the Associated Press, Ecos del Torbes, La Prensa de Lara, Telemundo, TVVenezuela, VIVOplay, [[VPItv]] and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.el-carabobeno.com/apevex-condena-brutal-ataque-a-periodistas-en-frontera-de-venezuela-lista-de-periodistas-agredidos-el-23feb/|title=Apevex condena brutal ataque a periodistas en frontera de Venezuela. Lista de agresiones el 23Feb|date=25 February 2019|website=[[El Carabobe\u00f1o]]|language=es |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSwedish reporter [[Annika Hernroth-Rothstein]] reported to the National Assembly that she was violently threatened, ransacked and beaten by pro-Maduro paramilitary groups known as [[Colectivo (Venezuela)|colectivos]] on 23 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/asamblea-nacional/periodista-sueca-relato-desde-que-fue-amenazada-por-los-colectivos_272747|title=Periodista sueca relat\u00f3 desde la AN que fue amenazada por los colectivos|date=27 February 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref> Rothstein returned to Venezuela on 18 April, but she was briefly detained at the airport by the [[Venezuelan National Guard]] (GNB) and was subsequently deported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/gnb-deporto-periodista-sueca-cuando-llego-maiquetia_279680|title=GNB deport\u00f3 a periodista sueca cuando lleg\u00f3 a Maiquet\u00eda|date=18 April 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/venezuela/annika-rothstein-venezuela-deporta-periodista-sueca-denuncio-agresion-colectivos-chavistas-noticia-628027|title=Venezuela deporta a periodista sueca que denunci\u00f3 agresi\u00f3n de colectivos chavistas|date=18 April 2019|website=El Comercio|language=es|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Jorge Ramos (news anchor)|Jorge Ramos]], who ''[[The Guardian]]'' described as \"arguably the best-known journalist in the Spanish-speaking world\", was detained along with his [[Univisi\u00f3n]] crew members during an interview with Maduro on 25 February.<ref name=CNNRamos>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/feb/25/jorge-ramos-univision-detained-venezuela-maduro-interview |title= Univision's Jorge Ramos detained in Venezuela after Maduro interview, network says |author=Daniels, Joe Parkin|date= 26 February 2019|work= [[The Guardian]] |access-date= 26 February 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Univisi\u00f3n equipment and materials were confiscated by Venezuelan authorities.<ref name=CNNRamos/> During the interview, Maduro denied that a humanitarian crisis existed in Venezuela, which prompted Ramos to show Maduro images of Venezuelan children eating from a garbage truck and asking again if a crisis existed.<ref name=CNNRamos/><ref name= CNBCRamos>{{Cite news |url= https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/26/univision-says-team-held-in-venezuela-while-interviewing-president.html |title= Univision says team briefly held in Venezuela after Maduro interview |date=25 February 2019 |work= [[CNBC]]|access-date= 26 February 2019}}</ref> After being released, Ramos stated that he and his group were held because this question bothered Maduro.<ref name= CNNRamos/> The Univisi\u00f3n team was informed they would be deported, Maduro's Minister of Information [[Jorge Rodr\u00edguez (politician)|Jorge Rodr\u00edguez]] described the incident as a \"cheap show\".<ref name=CNBCRamos/>\n\nTelemundo journalist Daniel Garrido was detained for eight hours by SEBIN on 26 February and was later irregularly released on a side street in Caracas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/02/26/sebin-libera-a-daniel-garrido-periodista-de-telemundo-tras-ocho-horas-de-detencion-arbitraria/|title=Sebin libera a Daniel Garrido, periodista de Telemundo, tras ocho horas de detenci\u00f3n arbitraria|date=26 February 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe journalist and dissident Chavist [[Al\u00ed Dom\u00ednguez]] was kidnapped on 28 February; he was found comatose on the roadside of a major highway on the morning of the next day, though this was not released even to his family until several days later, shortly before he died as a result of injuries of beating and suspected torture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodiario.com.ni/internacionales/487247-muerte-periodista-ali-dominguez-venezuela/|title=Muerte periodista: Ali Dominguez|website=El Nuevo Diario|language=es|access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== March blackouts ===\n{{Further|2019 Venezuelan blackouts}}\n[[File:Luis Carlos D\u00edaz a La Represa (1).jpg|thumb|Venezuelan journalist Luis Carlos D\u00edaz was detained for 30 hours in May. He was accused of sabotaging the national power grid.]]\nUS freelance journalist Cody Weddle and his Venezuelan coworker Carlos Camacho were detained for half a day on 7 March after Weddle house was raided and his equipment confiscated by military counterintelligence forces. US diplomats demanded Venezuelan authorities for Weddle's release. Weddle was deported afterwards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/venezuela/article227175764.html|title=U.S. journalist briefly detained, then released in Venezuela amid continued unrest|date=6 March 2019|website=Miami Herald|access-date=7 March 2019}}<br />* {{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/venezuelan-counterintelligence-forces-raid-home-of-us-journalist-take-him-into-custody/2019/03/06/0a1508ca-402e-11e9-85ad-779ef05fd9d8_story.html|title=Venezuela expels German ambassador, detains U.S. journalist|last=Sheridan|first=Mary Beth|date=6 March 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=7 March 2019}}<br />* {{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-politics-germany-idUSKCN1QN224|title=Venezuela releases American journalist after full day in custody:...|last=Sequera|first=Vivian|date=7 March 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=7 March 2019|last2=Pons|first2=Corina|language=en}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Venezuelan blackouts]], Venezuelan\u2013Spanish journalist {{ill|Luis Carlos D\u00edaz|es}} was at his house when he was arrested by SEBIN forces, and taken along with his electronic equipment to [[El Helicoide]]. He said he had been physically attacked and that the intelligence agents had taken money from his house without reporting it. A group accompanied by his wife, journalist [[Naky Soto]], protested in front of the prosecutor office. [[Michelle Bachelet]], head of the UN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights, was in Caracas at that time and tweeted concern about the detention.<ref name=\"Bachelettweet\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mbachelet/status/1105517564686409729|title=Estoy profundamente preocupada por la presunta detenci\u00f3n del reputado periodista @LuisCarlos por parte de los servicios de inteligencia venezolanos, y por su bienestar. La misi\u00f3n t\u00e9cnica de @ONU_derechos que se encuentra en Caracas pidi\u00f3 a las autoridades acceso urgente a D\u00edaz.|last=Bachelet|first=Michelle|date=12 March 2019|website=@mbachelet on Twitter|language=es|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> The Spanish embassy in Caracas also contacted the government for information. D\u00edaz was accused as an accomplice in a plot to cause the electricity outage, he was charged with instigation of a crime and is not allowed to leave Venezuela.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-12/venezuelan-police-arrest-prominent-journalist-as-he-cycles-home|title=Venezuela Police Free Noted Journalist After Overnight Detention|last=Laya|first=Patricia|date=12 March 2019|work=Bloomberg|access-date=13 March 2019|last2=Orozco|first2=Jose}}</ref> He is also forbidden to participate in protests or to give statements to the media, and he must appear before court every eight days.<ref name=\"bbcLCDiaz\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-47539021|title=Decretan libertad condicional al periodista venezolano Luis Carlos D\u00edaz, detenido en Caracas por el servicio de inteligencia|date=13 March 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\n''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]'' Polish journalist, Tomasz Surdel, was briefly detained, threatened, and beaten, by police [[Venezuelan National Police#Special Actions Force|Special Actions Force]] (FAES) during the blackout, according to the Venezuelan press workers union.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-politics-reporter/polish-journalist-beaten-by-venezuelan-police-press-union-idUSKCN1QW2GR|title=Polish journalist beaten by Venezuelan police: press union|last=Ellsworth|first=Brian |date=15 March 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=15 March 2019|last2=Orozco|first2=Jose}}</ref> The newspaper's website said it had received complaints about his reporting on Maduro from the Venezuelan Embassy in Warsaw, and that he was not arrested but was viciously beaten and left by the side of the road.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.foxnews.com/world/polish-journalist-in-venezuela-tormented-viciously-beaten-by-national-police-his-employer-says |title= Polish journalist in Venezuela tormented, viciously beaten by government 'death squad,' his employer says |author= Llorente, Elizabeth |work= Fox News |date= 19 March 2019 |accessdate= 20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nGerman journalist [[Billy Six]], who was detained in El Helicoide since 17 November 2018 charged of espionage, rebellion and security violations, was allowed to leave Venezuela on 16 March. He must report to court every 15 days and he cannot speak to the media about his detention. Reporters Without Borders had previously considered the allegations unproven and called for his release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/billy-six-nach-freilassung-auf-dem-weg-nach-deutschland-a-1258288.html|title=Nach Freilassung in Venezuela: Deutscher Billy Six auf dem Weg nach Deutschland|date=17 March 2019|work=Spiegel|access-date=17 March 2019|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/venezuela-releases-german-journalist-billy-six-from-jail/a-47943133|title=Venezuela releases German journalist Billy Six from jail|date=16 March 2019|website=Deutsche Welle|access-date= 17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Venemundo Web'' reporter Dayana Krays was threatened with a gun by colectivos on 31 March.<ref name=cpjdanilog>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/04/venezuelan-police-detain-reporter-danilo-gil-while.php|title=Venezuelan police detain reporter Danilo Gil while covering protests, charge him with resisting authority|date=4 April 2019|website=CPJ|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the second wave of blackouts, Venezuelan journalist Danilo Alberto Gil was detained in Zulia on 30 March while covering the protests in [[Ciudad Ojeda]]. At the time of the arrest, he was recording a video of the police repression against protesters and an attempt of detention of National Assembly members. Gil was released on 1 April judged with charges of resistance to authority and he is barred from leaving the country.<ref name=cpjdanilog />\n\n=== May 2019 ===\nA National Assembly session was held on 7 May to discuss a proposal for Venezuela's return to [[Inter-American Treaty of Reciprocal Assistance]] (TIAR). News outlets were prevented to cover the session by police forces and some journalists were harassed by Maduro supporters.<ref name=washingtonpost8may /> NetBlocks also reported internet outages during the session live-stream.<ref name=washingtonpost8may />\n\nOn the same day, Spanish journalist Joan Guirado covering the crisis in Venezuela for [[Okdiario]] was arrested and held for hours by SEBIN, and later expelled from Venezuela.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/05/08/actualidad/1557291915_187567.html|title=Un periodista espa\u00f1ol que cubr\u00eda la crisis de Venezuela denuncia su expulsi\u00f3n del pa\u00eds|date=8 May 2019|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=8 May 2019|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\nUnder the alleged threat of the presence of an explosive, the entry to the parliament was blocked by the GNB and SEBIN on 14 May.<ref name=BlockANF24>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190514-venezuelan-security-services-block-lawmakers-parliament|title=Venezuelan security services block lawmakers from parliament|date=14 May 2019|website=France 24|access-date=16 May 2019}}</ref> The National Assembly session of  that day, concerning the detention of their vicepresident Edgar Zambrano, had to be rescheduled for the next day.<ref name=BlockANreuters>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-politics-idUSKCN1SK288|title=Venezuela's top court accuses more lawmakers of treason; congress building closed|date=15 May 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=16 May 2019}}</ref>  Jorge Millan, a National Assembly member, said that the report of \"bombs\" was false.<ref name=BlockANreuters /> Internet disruptions occurred during Guaido's public speech on the blockade.<ref name=netblocks14May/> Guaid\u00f3 tweeted \"they're trying to hold the legislative power hostage while the dictator entrenches himself alone in a palace where he shouldn't be\".<ref name=BlockANF24 /> The next day, media outlets were prevented from covering the parliamentary session. The security forces threatened reporters with detention if they did not clear out the vicinity of the parliament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/por-segunda-vez-consecutiva-la-asamblea-nacional-sesiono-sin-medios-de-comunicacion/|title=Por segunda vez consecutiva, la Asamblea Nacional sesion\u00f3 sin medios de comunicaci\u00f3n|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=Sammy Paola|date=15 May 2019|work=El Pitazo|access-date=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://efectococuyo.com/politica/gnb-prohibe-acceso-de-la-prensa-al-palacio-legislativo-por-tercera-vez-en-nueve-dias/|title=GNB proh\u00edbe acceso de la prensa al Palacio Legislativo por tercera vez en nueve d\u00edas|last=Le\u00f3n|first=Ibis|date=15 May 2019|work=Efecto Cocuyo|access-date=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe access to media outlets to congress was blocked again on 21<ref><{{cite news|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/asamblea-nacional/gnb-impide-ingreso-los-medios-comunicacion-asamblea-nacional_282950|title=GNB impide el ingreso de los medios de comunicaci\u00f3n a la Asamblea Nacional|date=21 May 2019|access-date=21 May 2019|language=es}}</ref> and on 28 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/alrededores-amanecen-militarizados-por-cuarta-semana-consecutiva_283641|title=Alrededores de la AN amanecen militarizados por cuarta semana seguida|date=28 May 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Iv\u00e1n Simonovis]]\u2014a former police commissioner arrested in November 2004 and accused by the [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] government of the violence that took place in Caracas during the 2002 [[Llaguno Overpass events]]<ref name=\"ElUniversal\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/nacional-y-politica/140529/cronologia-del-caso-ivan-simonovis|title=Cronolog\u00eda del caso Iv\u00e1n Simonovis|last=Dickson L\u00f3pez|first=Leandro|date=20 September 2014|newspaper=[[El Universal (Venezuela)|El Universal]]|accessdate=30 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930145447/http://www.eluniversal.com/nacional-y-politica/140920/cronologia-del-caso-ivan-simonovis|archive-date=30 September 2015|url-status=dead|last2=de la Rosa|first2=Alicia|language=Spanish}}</ref>\u2014left house arrest in May. Guaid\u00f3 said that security forces loyal to him released Simonovis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/mediation-in-norway-aims-to-resolve-venezuela-crisis/2019/05/16/61b487e0-7841-11e9-a7bf-c8a43b84ee31_story.html|title=Mediation in Norway aims to resolve Venezuela crisis|last=Torchia|first=Christopher|date=16 May 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref> Press workers from [[Caracol Televisi\u00f3n]], [[TV Venezuela]] and [[Venevisi\u00f3n]], were outside Simonovis house when his whereabouts were unknown. Five of the journalists were arbitrarily detained for three hours.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2019/05/16/el-servicio-de-inteligencia-chavista-retuvo-durante-mas-de-3-horas-a-5-periodistas-en-las-puertas-de-la-casa-del-preso-politico-liberado-por-juan-guaido-ivan-simonovis/|title=El servicio de inteligencia chavista retuvo durante m\u00e1s de 3 horas a 5 periodistas en las puertas de la casa del preso pol\u00edtico liberado por Juan Guaid\u00f3 Iv\u00e1n Simonovis|date=16 May 2019|access-date=18 May 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 May, The [[Human Rights Watch]]<ref name=HMMedina>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/05/21/venezuela-free-freelance-photojournalist|title=Venezuela: Free Freelance Photojournalist|date=21 May 2019|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> and the [[Committee to Protect Journalists|CPJ]]<ref name=CPJmedinamay>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/05/venezuela-imprisoned-jesus-medina-photojournalist.php|title=Human Rights Watch call on Venezuela to release Jes\u00fas Medina|date=21 May 2019|website=CPJ|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> called for the \"immediate release\" of the photojournalist Jes\u00fas Medina Ezaine held in [[Ramo Verde Prison]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/human-rights-watch-exige-liberacion-del-periodista-jesus-medina_283003|title=Human Rights Watch exige la liberaci\u00f3n del periodista Jes\u00fas Medina|date=21 May 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2019/05/21/el-comite-para-la-proteccion-de-los-periodistas-y-human-rights-watch-exigieron-que-el-regimen-de-nicolas-maduro-libere-al-comunicador-jesus-medina/|title=El Comit\u00e9 para la Protecci\u00f3n de los Periodistas y Human Rights Watch exigieron que el r\u00e9gimen de Nicol\u00e1s Maduro libere al comunicador Jes\u00fas Medina|date=21 May 2019|website=Infobae|language=es|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>  Medina was first detained in October 2017 alongside journalist Roberto di Matteo of Italy and Filippo Rossi of Switzerland while reporting at Tocor\u00f3n penitentiary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/italian-swiss-journalists-among-3-detained-venezuela-n808846|title=Italian, Swiss journalists among 3 detained in Venezuela|date=8 October 2017|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=cpj2017medina>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2017/11/venezuelan-photographer-goes-missing-following-thr.php|title=Venezuelan photographer goes missing following threats|date=6 November 2017|website=CPJ|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref> After the detention, Medina went missing, according to the security forces, he was not held at their headquarters.<ref name=cpj2017medina /> Medina later appeared in November, left in a highway, he reported how he was tortured and threatened to death by his abductors.<ref name=HMMedina /> A team of journalists was working in an investigative project at at Caracas hospital in August 2018 when Medina was arrested again.<ref name=CPJmedinamay /> He was charged with inciting hate, illegal enrichment, and criminal association.<ref name=HMMedina /> On 2 May 2019, his preliminary hearing\u2014that has to take place 45 days at most after a detention\u2014was delayed for an eighth time.<ref name=HMMedina /> \"Venezuelan authorities should immediately drop the absurd charges against Jes\u00fas Medina and stop finding pretexts to prolong his pretrial detention\", said CPJ coordinator Nathalie Southwick.<ref name=HMMedina /> Medina was finally released in January 2020; he suffered from dental and vision problems while in detention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2020/01/venezuelan-photojournalist-jesus-medina-released-a.php|title=Venezuelan photojournalist Jes\u00fas Medina released after 16 months in prison|date=7 January 2020|website=CPJ|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>\n\n=== June\u2013August 2019 ===\nNews outlets were able to cover the National Assembly session on 4 June with the help of the members of the parliament. The media workers had to force their way through the blockade created by National Guardsmen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/periodistas-lograron-entrar-parlamento-tras-forcejeo-con-gnb_284313|title=Periodistas lograron ingresar al Parlamento tras forcejeo con la GNB|last=Brito|first=Estefani|date=4 June 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nJournalists had to force their way into parliament again on 18 June.<ref name=\"elpitazoAN18J\">{{Cite web|url=https://elpitazo.net/politica/diputados-rompieron-cerco-militar-y-dieron-acceso-a-la-prensa-a-la-an/|title=Diputados rompieron cerco militar y dieron acceso a la prensa a la AN|date=18 June 2019|website=El Pitazo|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Power outages and internet disruptions followed during the parliamentary session.<ref name=netblocks18June /><ref name=elpitazoAN18J />\n\n[[Braulio Jatar]], Chilean-Venezuelan journalist and lawyer jailed in 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/data/people/braulio-jatar/index.php|title=Braulio Jatar|date=2018|website=CPJ|access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> after accusing and protesting against Maduro for money laundering, was given conditional release on 5 July, the same day as the release of [[Detention of Maria Lourdes Afiuni|Maria Lourdes Afiuni]] and 20 students, according to Bachelet.<ref name=ReutersAfiuniJatar>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-un-prisoners-idUSKCN1U016V|title=Venezuela frees judge, journalist, 20 students: U.N|last=Nebehay|first=Stephanie|date=5 July 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> The releases happened after the publication of a [[United Nations]] report on government-backed death squads and the petition from Bachelet to Maduro administration to release government dissidents.<ref name=ReutersAfiuniJatar/> Afiuni's brother and Jatar said that they had not received official notices from Venezuela's judiciary.<ref name=ReutersAfiuniJatar/> Jatar was officially released on 8 July but he has to present himself before a court every 15 days and he cannot leave [[Nueva Esparta]] state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/07/venezuelan-journalist-braulio-jatar-conditionally-.php|title=Venezuelan journalist Braulio Jatar conditionally released, barred from leaving country|date=8 July 2019|website=CPJ|access-date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July, ''La Verdad'' Venezuelan journalist Wilmer Quintana Garc\u00eda was detained on charges of \"incitement or promotion hate\" under the Venezuelan [[Law against Hatred]].<ref name=CPJquintana>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/08/venezuelan-authorities-detain-wilmer-quintana-for-.php|title=Venezuelan authorities detain Wilmer Quintana for Facebook posts under anti-hate law|date=12 August 2019|website=CPJ|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref> Quintana Garc\u00eda used his personal Facebook and Twitter accounts to report on corruption allegations carried out by [[Gu\u00e1rico]] governor Jos\u00e9 Manuel Vasquez and president of Alimentos Gu\u00e1rico Emilio \u00c1vila.<ref name=CPJquintana /> The allegations included the mismanagement of funds to resupply gas services and the resale of [[Local Committees for Supply and Production|CLAP boxes]] at a higher price.<ref name=CPJquintana /> The CPJ denounced the arrest indicating that \"allegations of corruption against public officials are not hate speech\".<ref name=CPJquintana /> In August, Quintana Garc\u00eda was taken to a hospital due to a possible cardiac arrest.<ref name=CPJquintana />\n\nThe Venezuelan Press Workers Union (SNTP) denounced and condemned attacks committed by members of Juan Guaid\u00f3's team against at least seven press worker during an activity in [[Maracay]], [[Aragua|Aragua state]], on 31 August, stating that they were verbally and physically attacked. The Association of Venezuelan Journalists Abroad (APEVEX), declaring that \"Venezuelan journalists already had enough of the attacks by the regime to now also be victims of the interim government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntn24.com/america-latina/venezuela/gremio-denuncia-agresion-periodistas-por-parte-del-equipo-de-guaido-110346|title=Gremio denuncia agresi\u00f3n a periodistas por parte del equipo de Guaid\u00f3|date=2019-08-31|website=NTN24 {{!}} www.ntn24.com|language=es|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elimpulso.com/2019/09/02/sntp-denuncio-agresion-a-periodistas-por-parte-del-equipo-de-guaido-2sep/|title=SNTP denunci\u00f3 agresi\u00f3n a periodistas por parte del equipo de Guaid\u00f3 #2Sep|last=Ar\u00e9valo|first=Jos\u00e9 E.|date=2019-09-02|website=El Impulso|language=es|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref> Guaid\u00f3 apologized for the incident, assuring that he would take the necessary actions to prevent it from happening again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/la-humanidad/guaido-tomara-acciones-sobre-su-equipo-de-seguridad-tras-agresion-a-periodistas/|title=Guaid\u00f3 tomar\u00e1 \"acciones\" sobre su equipo de seguridad tras agresi\u00f3n a periodistas|date=2019-09-01|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venezuelaaldia.com/2019/09/01/presidente-e-guaido-se-disculpo-por-agresion-a-medios-en-aragua/|title=Presidente (E) Guaid\u00f3 se disculp\u00f3 por agresi\u00f3n a medios en Aragua|date=2019-09-01|website=Venezuela al dia|language=es|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n=== November-December 2019 ===\nSecurity forces from the Venezuelan military counterintelligence ([[Direcci\u00f3n General de Contrainteligencia Militar|DGCIM]]) entered ''Entorno Digital'', a press office, on 19 November afternoon and detained its employees. The office director stated that he was not made aware of the justification for the detentions. Between the detainees there were members of news websites ''Caraota Digital'' and [[VPItv|''VPITv'']]. The press workers were released some hours later during the night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lta.reuters.com/articulo/venezuela-politica-prensa-idLTAKBN1XU056-OUSLT|title=Liberados trabajadores de la prensa en Caracas: sindicato - Reuters|date=19 November 2019|website=Reuters|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor 10 hours, SEBIN agents raided the offices of {{Interlanguage link|Venepress|es}}, a media owned by [[Telecaribe]]. Afterwards, the media was shutdown indefinitely by the authorities without warrants nor government authorization for the raids, according to Venepress lawyers. Venepress news editor, Israel Barbuzano, suspects that the closures are part of an offensive against Telecaribe president who has supported Juan Guaid\u00f3 in opinion columns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/12/venezuelan-intelligence-services-raid-shutter-vene.php|title=Venezuelan intelligence services raid, shutter news outlets Venepress and Telecaribe|website=cpj.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n=== January 2020 Parliament vote disrupted ===\nDuring the [[2020 Venezuelan National Assembly Delegated Committee election]], to choose the president of the National Assembly, independent journalists were also impeded from covering the event. Maduro's Ministry of Information, which has no relationship to the National Assembly, allowed reporters from state-run media to enter the legislative palace.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-venezuela-politics-idUKKBN1Z40J8|title=Venezuela opposition pushes to re-elect Guaido as congress chief|date=2020-01-05|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-05|language=en}}</ref> Other reporters were not allowed in and told to watch it on a live feed from outside.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-venezuela-politics-idUKKBN1Z40J8|title=Venezuela opposition pushes to re-elect Guaido as congress chief|date=2020-01-05|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-05|language=en}}</ref>\n\nState communications service [[CANTV]] reportedly blocked access to social media sites [[Twitter]], [[Facebook]], [[Instagram]], and [[YouTube]] on the day of the election. Block tracking website [[NetBlocks]] reported that the block began as the National Assembly session did, criticizing this.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnacional.com/venezuela/cantv-bloquea-las-redes-sociales-para-censurar-sesion-de-la-asamblea-nacional/|title=Cantv bloquea las redes sociales para censurar la Asamblea Nacional|date=2020-01-05|website=EL NACIONAL|language=es|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\nIn a follow-up on 15 January, the entry to the parliament was blocked by police forces. Colectivos, pro-Maduro paramilitary groups, joined the scene and threatened lawmakers and journalists. Parallel to it, in [[Bolivar Plaza (Caracas)]], colectivos attacked a teachers strike. Some journalists were attacked with [[human waste]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/venezuela/colectivos-chavistas-lanzaron-orina-y-heces-a-periodistas-que-cubrian-protesta-de-maestros-en-venezuela-plaza-bolivar-caracas-noticia/|title=Colectivos chavistas lanzan orina y heces a periodistas que cubr\u00edan protesta de maestros en Venezuela|date=15 January 2020|website=El Comercio|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2020/01/15/el-regimen-de-nicolas-maduro-bloquea-la-asamblea-nacional-para-impedir-la-sesion-presidida-por-juan-guaido/|title=La Asamblea Nacional de Venezuela sesion\u00f3 en un recinto alternativo debido al bloqueo chavista y un ataque armado de colectivos|date=15 January 2020|website=Infobae|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Punto de Corte report ===\n''Punto de Corte'' journalists Johan \u00c1lvarez and Alexandra Vill\u00e1n did an undercover report about [[CANTV]], a major state owned telecommunication company, where they were able to infiltrate the main headquarters in Caracas with help of workers and showed several problems, including malfunctioning equipment and, as well as the lack of required air conditioning, which causes many problems experienced by users. After the report was published, the journalists were threatened and Punto de Corte was blocked in Venezuela. The day after the report was published, on 1 February, \u00c1lvarez and Vill\u00e1n were hit by a car in Baralt Avenue of Caracas while \u00c1lvarez was riding a motorcycle. \u00c1lvarez had a skull fracture and internal bleeding, while Vill\u00e1n received tibia and fibula fractures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntn24.com/america-latina/venezuela/tras-bloqueo-medio-digital-arrollado-periodista-venezolano-que-realizo|title=Tras bloqueo a medio digital: Arrollado periodista venezolano que realiz\u00f3 trabajo sobre crisis de Cantv|last=|first=|date=1 February 2020|website=[[NTN24]]|language=Spanish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cronica.uno/arrollados-dos-periodistas-del-portal-punto-de-corte-en-la-avenida-baralt/|title=Arrollados dos periodistas del portal Punto de Corte en la avenida Baralt|last=Marra|first=Yohana|date=1 February 2020|website=Cr\u00f3nica Uno|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acn.com.ve/arrollados-dos-periodistas-portal-punto-corte/|title=Arrollados dos periodistas del medio digital Punto de Corte|last=|first=|date=|website=Agencia Carabobe\u00f1a de Noticias|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n===Airport incident in February 2020===\nDuring Juan Guaid\u00f3 return to Venezuela in February 2020, after his second international tour, a group of supporters and pro-Maduro agitators received him in the airport. Despite the travel ban imposed on Guaid\u00f3, he was allowed to enter the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-politics/venezuelas-guaido-returns-home-after-diplomatic-world-tour-idUSKBN2052DE|title=Venezuela's Guaido returns home after diplomatic world tour|author=Sarah Kinosian|author2=Shaylim Valderrama|agency=Reuters|date=11 February 2020|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> During Guaid\u00f3's arrival, various media workers were insulted, harassed, robbed and physically aggressed by the agitators. According to the Venezuelan Press Working Union (SNTP), Venezuelan security forces were present and witnessed the attacks, but did not intervene.<ref name=airportcpj>{{cite news|url=https://cpj.org/2020/02/pro-government-groups-attack-reporters-covering-ju.php|title=Pro-government groups attack reporters covering Juan Guaid\u00f3\u2019s return to Venezuela|agency=CPJ|date=13 February 2020|access-date=26 February 2020}}}</ref> Between the reported incidents there were two reporters that were punched and kicked in the face and a female journalist that was bitten by an agitator.<ref name=airportcpj/> Videos and photos of the events circulated over social media.<ref name=airportcpj/> A SNTP worker reported that some agitators carried knifes and razors and threatened journalists.<ref name=airportcpj/>\n\nTwo days later, when journalists were going to file the complaint to the authorities, security forces impeded their access to the prosecutor office.<ref name=airportcpj/>\n===During coronavirus disease pandemic ===\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela}}\n\n==Foreign censorship on the crisis==\nThe authorities of [[China]], supporters of the Maduro government, have censored information about the presidential crisis according to [[Radio Free Asia]].<ref name=RFAchinacensor>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/venezuela-online-02112019144205.html|title=China Targets Twitter Users Critical of Venezuela's Maduro|date= 11 February 2019|website=[[Radio Free Asia]]|access-date= 11 February 2019}}</ref> Reports from China state that Chinese citizens who criticize Maduro on social media are punished or fined, with economist He Jiangbing saying that the Chinese government is \"trying to prevent another [[color revolution]] ... because Venezuela and China are very similar\".<ref name=RFAchinacensor />\n\nAfter the news website [[Runrunes|Runrun.es]] published a report on extrajudicial killings by the [[Bolivarian National Police]], on 25 May, the Venezuelan ''Press and Society Institute'' (IPYS \u2013 {{lang-es|Instituto de Prensa y Sociedad}}) pointed out that the website was out of service due to an \"uncached request attack\", denouncing that it originated from [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Runrunes es v\u00edctima de ataques cibern\u00e9ticos tras reportaje sobre las FAES |url=https://talcualdigital.com/index.php/2019/05/27/runrunes-es-victima-de-ataques-ciberneticos-por-reportaje-sobre-las-faes/ |agency=Tal Cual |date=27 May 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/venezuelan-journalists-report-on-their-own-survival/a-49197707|title=Venezuelan journalists report on their own survival|last=Ole|first=Tangen Jr.|date=19 June 2019|work=Deutsche Welle|access-date=24 June 2019}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://espaciopublico.ong/el-apagon-tambien-fue-informativo/#.XLdm_pMzY6W|date=12 March 2019|title=El apag\u00f3n tambi\u00e9n fue informativo|access-date=17 April 2019|work=Espacio P\u00fablico|language=es}}\n\n{{Bolivarian Venezuela Crisis|state=collapsed}}\n{{Venezuela topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Censorship in Venezuela|Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2019 in politics]]\n[[Category:2019 in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Crisis in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:January 2019 events in South America]]\n[[Category:Political history of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\nThere has been '''[[censorship in Venezuela|censorship and media control]] during the 2019-2020 [[Venezuelan presidential crisis]]'''.\n\nA crisis concerning who is the legitimate [[President of Venezuela]] began on 10 January 2019, when the opposition-majority [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] declared that incumbent [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]]'s [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election|2018 reelection]] was invalid and the body declared its president, [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]], to be [[acting president]] of the nation. The process and results of the May [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election]] were widely disputed.<ref name=\"BriefingNYT\">{{cite news |title= Climate Change, U.S. Shutdown, Michael Cohen: Your Friday Briefing |author= Bullock, Penn |work= New York Times (Online) |date= 10 January 2019 |via=ProQuest |quote= President Nicol\u00e1s Maduro was inaugurated for a second term after an election last year that was widely considered illegitimate\u2014and despite a plummeting economy and skyrocketing violence, hunger and migration.}}</ref> The National Assembly declared Maduro illegitimate on the day of his [[Second inauguration of Nicol\u00e1s Maduro|second inauguration]], citing the 1999 [[Constitution of Venezuela]] enacted under [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], Maduro's predecessor; in response, the pro-Maduro [[Supreme Tribunal of Justice (Venezuela)|Supreme Tribunal of Justice]] said the National Assembly's declaration was unconstitutional.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-46952641|title=El Tribunal Supremo de Justicia de Venezuela declara \"inconstitucional\" a la Asamblea Nacional y anula el nombramiento de Juan Guaid\u00f3 como su presidente|date=21 January 2019|work=BBC Mundo|accessdate=29 January 2019|language=es}}</ref>\n\nMaduro's government states that the crisis is a \"''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]'' led by the [[United States]] to topple him and control [[Oil reserves in Venezuela|the country's oil reserves]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.presidencia.gob.ve/Site/Web/Principal/paginas/classMostrarEvento3.php?id_evento=12708|title=Canciller Arreaza advierte que objetivo de plan golpista es el petr\u00f3leo venezolano|publisher=presidencia.gob.ve|accessdate=30 January 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.europapress.es/internacional/noticia-maduro-afirma-petroleo-principal-motivo-presion-eeuu-contra-venezuela-20190130061636.html|title=Maduro afirma que el petr\u00f3leo es el principal motivo de la presi\u00f3n de EEUU contra Venezuela|publisher=Europa Press|accessdate=30 January 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref> Guaid\u00f3 denies the coup allegations, saying peaceful volunteers back his movement.<ref name= ReadyDie>{{cite news |url= https://www.euronews.com/2019/02/18/i-m-ready-to-die-for-my-country-s-future-juan-guaido-tells-euronews |work= Euronews |title= 'I'm ready to die for my country's future,' Juan Guaido tells Euronews |author= Borges, Anelise |date= 18 February 2019 |accessdate= 18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince the beginning of the presidential crisis, Venezuela has been exposed to frequent \"information blackouts\", periods without access to internet or other news services during important political events.<ref name=Timearticle /><ref name=cpj30april/> Since January, the National Assembly and Guaido's speeches are regularly disrupted, television channels and radio programs have been censored and many journalists have been illegally detained.<ref name=Timearticle /> The Venezuelan press workers union reported that in 2019, 40&nbsp;journalists had been illegally detained as of 12 March.<ref name=\"Escalona\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.elimpulso.com/2019/03/13/173-agresiones-a-trabajadores-de-la-prensa-contabiliza-comision-de-medios-de-la-asamblea-nacional-13mar/|title=173 agresiones a trabajadores de la prensa contabiliza Comisi\u00f3n de Medios de la Asamblea Nacional #13Mar|last=Escalona|first=Jos\u00e9|date=13 March 2019|work=El Impulso|access-date=19 March 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref> As of June 2019, journalists have been denied access to seven sessions of the National Assembly by the National Guard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/06/soldiers-block-press-access-to-venezuelan-parliame.php|title=Soldiers block press access to Venezuelan parliament|date=25 June 2019|website=CPJ|access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nMost Venezuelan television channels are controlled by the state, and information unfavorable to the government is not covered completely.<ref name=Timearticle /> Newspapers and magazines are scarce, as most are unable to afford paper to print.<ref name=Timearticle /> The underfunded web infrastructure has led to slow Internet connection speeds.<ref name=Timearticle />\n\nThe information blackouts have promoted the creation of underground news coverage that is usually broadcast through social media and instant message services like [[WhatsApp]].<ref name=Timearticle /> The dependence of Venezuelans on social media has also promoted the spread of disinformation and pro-Maduro propaganda.<ref name=Timearticle />\n\nVenezuela got the rank 148 of 180 in the [[Press Freedom Index|World Press Freedom Index]] of [[Reporters Without Borders]] in 2019. The country went down five places since 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/5572179/reporters-without-borders-rsf-world-press-freedom-2019/|title=2019 World Press Freedom Index Shows Global Decline|last=Leung|first=Hilary|date=18 April 2019|website=Time|access-date=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Inter-American Commission on Human Rights]] (IACHR) has made a call to Maduro administration to reestablish TV and radio channels that have been closed, cease on the restrictions to Internet access, and to protect the rights of journalists.<ref name=OASmay>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/en/iachr/expression/showarticle.asp?artID=1140&lID=1|title=The Office of the Special Rapporteur condemns closure of Radio Caracas Radio 750 AM, the censorship of television channels, restrictions on the Internet, and the arrest of journalists in Venezuela|date=15 May 2019|website=Organization of American States|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=OAStalcual>{{Cite web|url=https://talcualdigital.com/index.php/2019/05/14/cidh-condeno-cierre-de-medios-de-comunicacion-y-detenciones-de-periodistas/|title=CIDH conden\u00f3 cierre de medios de comunicaci\u00f3n y detenciones de periodistas|date=15 May 2019|website=TalCual|language=es|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Internet, television, and radio ==\n{{More|Block of Wikipedia in Venezuela}}\n\n=== 2019 ===\nSeveral sources reported that starting 12 January 2019 until 18 January,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archivo.elpitazo.net/otras-noticias/wikipedia-ya-esta-disponible-venezuela-tras-bloqueado-cantv/|title=Wikipedia ya est\u00e1 disponible para Venezuela tras ser bloqueado por Cantv!|date=19 January 2019|website=El Pitazo|language=es|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ipysvenezuela.org/2019/01/29/from-the-blocking-of-wikipedia-to-social-media-venezuelas-political-crisis/|title=From the blocking of Wikipedia to Social Media: Venezuela\u2019s Political Crisis|date=29 January 2019|website=IPYS Venezuela|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> internet access to Wikipedia (in all languages) was blocked in Venezuela<ref>{{cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/wikipedia-blocked-in-venezuela-as-internet-controls-tighten-XaAwR08M|title=Wikipedia blocked in Venezuela as internet controls tighten|date=12 January 2019|website=NetBlocks|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113134629/https://netblocks.org/reports/wikipedia-blocked-in-venezuela-as-internet-controls-tighten-XaAwR08M|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/usuarios-cantv-denuncian-que-acceso-wikipedia-esta-bloqueado_266182|title=Usuarios de Cantv denuncian que el acceso a Wikipedia est\u00e1 bloqueado|date=12 January 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref> after [[:es:Juan Guaid\u00f3|Guaid\u00f3's page]] on the [[Spanish Wikipedia]] was edited to show him as president.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://efectococuyo.com/principales/nota-de-juan-guaido-en-wikipedia-cambia-37-veces-en-dos-horas-y-nueve-minutos-este-11e/|title=Nota de Juan Guaid\u00f3 en Wikipedia cambia 37 veces en dos horas y nueve minutos este #11E|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=Spanish|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> The block mainly affected the users of the state-run [[CANTV]], the national telecommunications company and largest provider of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wikimedia_ve/status/1085510793226010625|title=Sobre el bloqueo en Wikipedia: Comunicado Oficial|last=Wikimedia Venezuela|date=16 January 2019|website=Twitter|language=es|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref> Several media outlets have suggested that Wikipedia directly or indirectly was taking sides with either group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noticierodigital.com/2019/01/wikipedia-ya-coloca-guaido-presidente-interino-venezuela/|title=Perfil de Guaid\u00f3 en Wikipedia lo se\u00f1ala como presidente interino de Venezuela|date=11 January 2019|website=Noticiero Digital|language=Spanish|trans-title=Profile of Guaid\u00f3 in Wikipedia designates him as acting president of Venezuela|accessdate=13 January 2019}}<br />* {{cite web|url=http://www.caraotadigital.net/nacionales/cantv-wikipedia-guaido/|title=Cantv habr\u00eda bloqueado acceso a Wikipedia donde se se\u00f1al\u00f3 que Juan Guaid\u00f3 era \"presidente venezolano\".|date=12 January 2019|website=Venepress|language=Spanish|trans-title=CANTV reportedly blocked access to Wikipedia where it was claimed that Juan Guaid\u00f3 was \"Venezuelan president\".|accessdate=13 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190205044741/http://www.caraotadigital.net/nacionales/cantv-wikipedia-guaido/|archive-date=5 February 2019|url-status=dead}}<br />* {{cite web|url=http://www.2001.com.ve/en-la-agenda/199667/wikipedia-asume-que-juan-guaido-es-el-presidente-interino-de-venezuela-.html|title=Wikipedia asumi\u00f3 que Juan Guaid\u00f3 es el presidente interino de Venezuela|date=11 January 2019|website=Diario 2001|language=Spanish|trans-title=Wikipedia assumed that Juan Guaid\u00f3 is the acting president of Venezuela|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Netblocks-venezuela-social-block.png|thumb|left|[[NetBlocks]] showing blocks of [[Instagram]], [[Twitter]], and [[YouTube]] on 21 January 2019]]\nLater on 21 January, the day of a National Guard mutiny in Cotiza, internet access to some social media like [[Twitter]], [[Instagram]], and [[YouTube]] was reported blocked for CANTV users. The Venezuelan government denied it had engaged in blocking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/venezuela-social-media-restricted-amid-caracas-incident-zgBLoXA4|title=Social media outage and disruptions in Venezuela amid incident in Caracas|date=21 January 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/tecnologia/Bloqueo-Wikipedia_0_857415082.html|title=Venezuela y Wikipedia se contradicen: \u00bfbloque\u00f3 Maduro el acceso a la enciclopedia tras una \"guerra de ediciones\"?|last=del Castillo|first=Carlos|date=19 January 2019|website=El Diario|language=es|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 23 January protests, widespread internet outages for CANTV users were reported, with [[Wikipedia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wikimedia_ve/status/1088163301522132992|title=#23Ene  Reportamos, nuevamente, un bloqueo parcial para acceder a #Wikipedia en #Venezuela  desde @ContactoCantv y @SomosMovilnet_. Ay\u00fadanos a reportar: \u00bfpuedes acceder sin problemas? \u00a1Los leemos! @Wikimediapic.twitter.com/XeVOh8zWMM|last=Wikimedia Venezuela|date=23 January 2019|website=@wikimedia_ve|language=es|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref> [[Google Search]], [[Facebook]], Instagram, and many other social media platforms affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/major-internet-disruptions-in-venezuela-amid-protests-4JBQ2kyo|title=Major Internet disruptions in Venezuela amid protests|date=23 January 2019|website=[[NetBlocks]]|access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref> The widespread regional internet blackouts occurred again on 26 to 27 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/venezuela-total-internet-blackouts-qr8VeYy5|title=Evidence of regional internet blackouts across Venezuela|date=27 January 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/01/27/net-blocks-denuncia-bloqueos-de-internet-en-venezuela-durante-los-ultimos-dias/|title=Net Blocks denuncia bloqueos de Internet en Venezuela durante los \u00faltimos d\u00edas|date=27 January 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nCanal 24 Horas, a news channel owned by Chile's public broadcaster, [[Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile|TVN]], was removed from Venezuela's cable and satellite television operators by the state-run [[National Commission of Telecommunications]] (Conatel) on 24 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/01/24/denuncian-que-conatel-ordeno-eliminar-el-canal-de-24-horas-de-chile-de-las-cableoperadoras/|title=Denuncian que Conatel orden\u00f3 eliminar el canal de 24 Horas de Chile de las cableoperadoras|date=24 January 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=25 January 2019}}</ref> Conatel removed 24 Horas once again during 23 February conflicts in the Venezuelan frontier, no reason was given.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/sacaron-del-aire-canal-horas-por-transmitir-ingreso-ayuda-humanitaria_272030|title=Sacaron del aire canal 24 horas por transmitir ingreso de ayuda humanitaria|date=23 February 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince 22 January, Conatel has repeatedly advised against the promotion of violence and the disavowing of institutional authorities, according to the [[Law on Social Responsibility on Radio and Television]] imposed in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Conatel/status/1090956613740126210|title=Conoce el art\u00edculo 27 de la Ley Resorte|last=Venezuela|first=Conatel|date=31 January 2019|website=@Conatel|language=es|access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref> Some radio programs have been ordered off air, including Cesar Miguel Rond\u00f3n's radio program, one of the most listened-to programs in the country. Other programs have been temporarily canceled or received censorship warnings, including a threat to close private television and radio stations if they recognize Guaid\u00f3 as acting president or interim president of Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/entretenimiento/censura-emisoras-televisoras-plataformas-arrecio-desde-enero_268833|title=Censura a emisoras, televisoras y plataformas arreci\u00f3 desde el 22 de enero|last=Gonz\u00e1lez Mendoza|first=Isaac|date=31 January 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=31 January 2019}}<br />* {{cite web|url=http://www.ntn24.com/america-latina/venezuela/cesar-miguel-rondon-se-despide-de-la-radio-y-transmitira-programa-por|title=C\u00e9sar Miguel Rond\u00f3n se despide de la radio y transmitir\u00e1 programa por Periscope e Instagram|date=29 January 2019|website=NTN24 {{!}} www.ntn24.com|language=es|access-date=31 January 2019}}<br />* {{Cite news|url=http://www.ntn24.com/america-latina/venezuela/conatel-amenaza-con-cerrar-medios-privados-que-llamen-guaido-presidente|title=Conatel amenaza con cerrar a medios privados que llamen a Guaid\u00f3 presidente encargado|date=24 January 2019|work=[[NTN24]]|quote=Algunas radios y televisoras privadas del pa\u00eds han recibido una amenaza por parte de Conatel si reconocen al diputado Juan Guaid\u00f3 como presidente encargado o interino de Venezuela. [Some private radios and television stations in the country have received a threat from Conatel if they recognize deputy Juan Guaid\u00f3 as acting president or interim president of Venezuela.]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Venezuela Aid Live]] concert on 22 February, [[National Geographic (TV channel)|NatGeo]] and [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3 Internacional]] were removed from cable and satellite TV for broadcasting the concert.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/sacaron-del-aire-nat-geo-antena-por-transmitir-venezuela-aid-live_271906|title=Sacaron del aire Nat Geo y Antena 3 por transmitir el Venezuela Aid Live|date= 22 February 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date= 23 February 2019}}</ref> Access to YouTube was also blocked for CANTV users during the concert.<ref name=netblocksVAL>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/youtube-blocked-during-venezuela-aid-live-concert-3RyjdbAg|title=YouTube blocked during Venezuela Aid Live concert|date=22 February 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nWithout clear reason, Twitter was blocked for CANTV users on 27 February, and again on 4 March, with Guaido's return from his regional trip. The access to [[SoundCloud]] was also restricted all along between both dates. NetBlocks suspects that the first censorship on the 27th was related either to a SoundCloud recording published by Guaid\u00f3 on Twitter or to a viral video showing several delegates leaving the UN Human Rights Council meeting during [[Jorge Arreaza]] speech.<ref name=twitterblocked /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/twitter-and-soundcloud-blocked-in-venezuela-as-guaido-returns-noy994y3|title=Twitter and SoundCloud blocked in Venezuela as Guaid\u00f3 returns|date=4 March 2019|website=NetBlocks|language=en-US|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> Soundcloud access was restricted during the following 3 months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/analysis/mapping-the-implications-of-venezuelas-new-national-telecommunications-corporation-98aZgYAo|title=Mapping the implications of Venezuela's new National Telecommunications Corporation|date=24 May 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nWithout any official statement from Conatel, the German state owned TV channel, [[Deutsche Welle]] (DW) in Spanish, was blocked from Venezuelan cable networks from 14 to 15 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-germany-idUSKCN1RQ0GE|title=German state-owned TV says Venezuela blocked its Spanish channel|date=14 April 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=14 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-media-germany-idUSKCN1RR221|title=German state-owned TV says it returns to Venezuela screens|date=15 April 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref> Conatel had already censored the DW signal once before in 2018 during the broadcast of a documentary titled \"Venezuela\u2014Escape from a Failed State\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://efectococuyo.com/la-humanidad/restablecen-senal-de-la-televisora-alemana-dw-en-venezuela/|title=Restablecen se\u00f1al de la televisora alemana DW en Venezuela - Efecto Cocuyo|last=Gonzalez Mendoza|first=Isaac|date=15 April 2019|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/venezuela-temporarily-blocks-critical-dw-documentary/a-44977801|title=Venezuela temporarily blocks critical DW documentary|date=8 June 2018|website=Deutsche Welle|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Venezuelan uprising]] of 30 April, Juan Guaid\u00f3 led a group of civilian and military forces in an uprising against [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]]. Shortly after the announcement, NetBlocks reported that multiple social media and news websites were censored by the state-run [[CANTV]] internet provider.<ref name=\"netblocks30april\">{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/internet-services-restricted-in-venezuela-amid-military-uprising-xAG4RGBz|title=Internet services restricted in Venezuela amid military uprising|date=30 April 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref> Internet service was restored 20 minutes before a live speech of Nicol\u00e1s Maduro.<ref name=\"netblocks30april\" /> During the clashes, the signal of [[BBC World News]] and [[CNN]]  was pulled off air from all cable providers ordered by Conatel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/30/media/venezuela-cnn-bbc/index.html|title=CNN and BBC pulled off the air by Venezuela's government|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|date=30 April 2019|website=CNN|access-date=1 May 2019}}</ref> According to CNN, it was blocked one minute after its live feed showed government [[VN-4]]s running over protesters.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/videos/business/2019/04/30/orig-venezuela-cnn.cnn/video/playlists/around-the-world/ |publisher= CNN |date= 3 May 2019 |accessdate= 3 May 2019 |title= See the moment CNN was taken off air in Venezuela}}</ref> Venezuela's oldest private local radio station [[Radio Caracas Radio]] (RCR) was also ordered off air.<ref name=cpj30april>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/05/venezuelan-authorities-restrict-internet-block-out.php|title=Venezuelan authorities restrict internet, block outlets amid unrest|date=1 May 2019|website=CPJ|language=en|access-date=2 May 2019}}</ref> Broadcast issues and internet disruptions followed during the protests of 1 May.<ref name=cpj30april/>\n\n{{quote box|width=33%|\"The closing of media as a punishment for maintaining a critical editorial line, as well as the blocking of signals to avoid access to information of public interest, arbitrarily suppresses the right of all Venezuelans to express themselves and receive plural information, and it also constitutes a form of censorship\"|Edison Lanza, Special Rapporteur for Freedom of Expression of the [[Inter-American Commission on Human Rights|IACHR]], after the 30 April uprising|<ref name=OASmay />}}\n\nThe IACHR communication expressed that \"freedom of expression applies to the Internet in the same way as it does to all communication media\" and consider Internet restrictions as an \"extreme measure-analogous to the prohibition of a newspaper or a radio or television station\". The report emphasizes that \"such blockades or restrictions cannot be justified, not even for reasons of public order or national security\". The IACHR rapporteur also explained that the \"adjudication, revocation, and renewal of licenses must be established by law and guided by objective, clear, impartial, and public criteria compatible with a democratic society; the process must be transparent; the decision that grants or denies the request must be duly motivated; and be subject to adequate judicial control\".<ref name=OASmay /><ref name=OAStalcual />\n\n[[Committee to Protect Journalists]] (CPJ) South coordinator, Natalie Southwick, has criticized the recent situation in Venezuela: \"We are alarmed by the increasingly brazen censorship in Venezuela, including the repeated and selective restriction of internet access, a popular tool of authoritarian regimes. Venezuelan authorities should ensure that all internet platforms and news outlets\u2014digital, radio, and television\u2014are available to citizens seeking to access and share information\".<ref name=cpj30april/>\n\n[[Edgar Zambrano]] vice-minister of the National Assembly and ally of Guaid\u00f3 was detained by the [[Bolivarian Intelligence Service]] (SEBIN) on 8 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/world/americas/venezuela-opposition-zambrano-detained.html|title=Ally of Venezuelan opposition leader is detained, Guaid\u00f3 Says|author=Kurmanaev, Anatoly|date=8 May 2019|work=New York Times|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> During the three hours after his detention, NetBlocks reported disruption of YouTube and Google services for CANTV users.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/youtube-and-google-services-disrupted-in-venezuela-following-zambrano-ambush-PAYYwEAe|title=\nYouTube and Google services disrupted in Venezuela following Zambrano ambush|date=9 May 2019|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June, the Venezuelan news website ''[[La Patilla]]'' was charged with \"moral charges\" and a fine of 30 billion bolivars (about $5m dollars) after publishing an [[ABC News]] article<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/internacional/20150127/abci-venezuela-cabello-eeuu-201501262129.html|title=El jefe de seguridad del n\u00famero dos chavista deserta a EE.UU. y le acusa de narcotr\u00e1fico|last=Blasco|first=Emil J.|date=26 January 2015|website=ABC|language=es|access-date=8 June 2019}}</ref> about drug traffic in Venezuela, that implicated the president of the pro-Maduro [[2017 Constituent National Assembly]], [[Diosdado Cabello]]. The website director [[Alberto Federico Ravell]], supporter of Juan Guaid\u00f3, wrote that Cabello was engaging in \"judicial terrorism\". Cabello also added that he will take control of the website if it was unable to pay.<ref name=lapatilla30bn>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/venezuela-news-ordered-pay-5-million-key-regime-081209706.html|title=Venezuela news site ordered to pay $5 million to key regime figure|date=5 June 2019|website=Yahoo News|access-date=5 June 2019}}</ref> Cabello had previously tried to raise judicial processes against ABC and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' for accusations of drug trafficking, but the cases were rejected.<ref name=lapatilla30bn /> Nathalie Southwick (CPJ) considers that the measure against ''La Patilla'' is an \"attempt to bankrupt and shut down a critical outlet\" and provides an \"example of how the Venezuelan judicial system is being used to retaliate against critical media\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpj.org/2019/06/venezuelas-supreme-court-orders-la-patilla-to-pay-.php|title=Venezuela's Supreme Court orders La Patilla to pay US$5m in damages to Cabello|date=7 June 2019|website=CPJ|access-date=8 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nWithout any previous judiciary order, the access to online newspapers ''[[El Pitazo]]'' and ''[[Efecto Cocuyo]]'', through national and private internet providers, was blocked during the visit of the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]] (OHCHR) chief [[Michelle Bachelet]] to Venezuela in June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prodavinci.com/ipys-comprobo-bloqueos-a-el-pitazo-y-efecto-cocuyo/|title=IPYS comprob\u00f3 bloqueos a El Pitazo y Efecto Cocuyo|date=19 June 2019|website=Prodavinci|language=es|access-date=24 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/venezuela/2019/06/21/denuncian-a-movistar-venezuela-por-bloquear-medios-independientes-en-internet-por-instrucciones-del-regimen-de-maduro/|title=Denuncian a Movistar Venezuela por bloquear medios independientes en internet por instrucciones del r\u00e9gimen de Maduro|date=21 June 2019|website=Infobae|language=es|access-date=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 ===\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Venezuela]], the National Assembly created a webpage to provide information on the [[coronavirus disease]] to the public. The website was quickly restricted for CANTV users. The censorship was denounced by Guaid\u00f3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://efectococuyo.com/coronavirus/cantv-bloquea-web-informativa-sobre-el-covid-19-denuncia-venezuela-sin-filtro/|title=Cantv bloquea web informativa sobre el COVID-19, denuncia Venezuela Sin Filtro|last=Ferm\u00edn|first=Mar\u00eda Victoria|date=18 March 2020|website=Efecto Cocuyo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 1st April, the independent journalism site ''AlbertoNews'' was indefinitely restricted after a coverage of {{Interlanguage link|Operaci\u00f3n Tun Tun|es}} (Operation Knock-Knock)'',''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2020/04/01/netblocks-confirma-bloqueo-del-acceso-a-albertonews-en-aba-cantv-por-parte-del-regimen/|title=Netblocks confirma bloqueo del acceso a AlbertoNews en ABA Cantv por parte del r\u00e9gimen|date=1 April 2020|website=LaPatilla|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> a Maduro administration anti-terrorist operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/mundo/venezuela-operacion-tun-tun-maduro-dijo-justicia-va-llegar-terroristas-_0_BOHYwJurf.html|title=Venezuela: \"Operaci\u00f3n Tun Tun\", Maduro dijo que la justicia les va llegar a todos los \"terroristas\"|date=31 March 2020|website=Clar\u00edn|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Live speeches disrupted ===\nLive streams of the National Assembly sessions and Guaid\u00f3's speeches and appearances have been regularly disrupted for CANTV users since the end of January, mainly affecting access to streaming platforms like [[Periscope (app)|Periscope]], [[Bing (search engine)|Bing]], Twitter video, and YouTube, along with some other Google services.<ref name=Timearticle>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/5571504/venezuela-internet-press-freedom/|title=Inside the Battle to Get News to Venezuelans|last=Nugent|first=Clara|date=16 April 2019|website=Time|access-date=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=disruptionrecord>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/new-targeted-youtube-restriction-in-venezuela-WRAe3Pyg|title=New targeted YouTube restriction in Venezuela|date=7 March 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=Pompeopressconf>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/streaming-platforms-blocked-in-venezuela-as-pompeo-speaks-from-colombia-MYAEm7A3|title=Streaming platforms blocked in Venezuela as Pompeo speaks from Colombia|date=15 April 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=15 April 2019}}</ref> [[DNS blocking]] is employed to generate the disruptions.<ref name=\"Timearticle\" /> The longest block of YouTube to date started during an Assembly session on 6 March, lasting 20 hours.<ref name=disruptionrecord/><ref name=elnacional0704>{{Cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/detectan-restricciones-plataforma-youtube-venezuela_273724|title=Detectan restricciones de la plataforma Youtube en Venezuela|date=7 March 2019|website=El Nacional|language=es|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the events of 23 February to [[2019 shipping of humanitarian aid to Venezuela|ship of humanitarian aid to Venezuela]], Guaid\u00f3 and Colombian President [[Iv\u00e1n Duque M\u00e1rquez|Iv\u00e1n Duque]]'s evening speech in [[Las Tienditas Bridge]] was similarly blocked for CANTV users in Venezuela.<ref name=\"netblocks23f\" /> More disruptions recurred during the [[Lima Group]] session on the 24th and during the US Vice President [[Mike Pence]]'s speech on 25 February.<ref name=\"netblocks23f\" />\n\nAnother disruption on April 15, affecting only CANTV users, occurred during the live stream of the press conference about Venezuela's crisis of US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] and Duque in [[C\u00facuta]].<ref name=\"Pompeopressconf\" />\n\nVenezuelan politician [[Leopoldo L\u00f3pez]], detained during the [[2014 Venezuelan protests|2014 protests]] and under house arrest by Maduro administration was released by pro-Guaid\u00f3 military during the 30 April uprising.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/04/30/venezuelas-imprisoned-opposition-leader-reappears-amid-uprising/|title=Leopoldo L\u00f3pez, Venezuela\u2019s imprisoned opposition leader, reappears amid uprising|last=Tamkin|first=Emily|date=30 April 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=4 May 2019}}</ref> L\u00f3pez and his family sought refuge in the Spanish embassy in Caracas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2019/05/01/inenglish/1556713845_723006.html|title=Venezuelan opposition leader seeks refuge in Spanish embassy in Caracas|last=Abell\u00e1n|first=Luc\u00eda|date=2 May 2019|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=4 May 2019|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> On 2 May, the disruption of internet services resumed during a press-conference<ref name=\"Netblocks2and3may\" /> where L\u00f3pez spoke about his discussions with mid-military officers to oppose Maduro administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/may/03/spain-leopoldo-lopez-venezuela-opposition-politician-diplomatic-compound|title=Spain will not remove Venezuelan opposition figure from its embassy|last=Graham-Harrison|first=Emma|date=3 May 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=4 May 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+Disrupted live streamed speeches in 2019-2020\n!Year\n!Month\n!Day\n!Event\n|-\n| rowspan=\"36\" |2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" |January\n|27\n|Guaido's speech<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/venezuela-total-internet-blackouts-qr8VeYy5|title=Evidence of regional internet blackouts across Venezuela|date=27 January 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|29\n|National Assembly session<ref>{{cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/venezuela-national-assembly-live-streams-disrupted-4M8JQvy0|title=Venezuela National Assembly live streams disrupted|date=29 January 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" |February\n|12\n|Guaid\u00f3's speech during International Youth Day<ref>{{cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/disruptions-in-venezuela-affecting-youtube-and-other-services-during-political-rally-WJBZda86|title=Disruptions in Venezuela affecting YouTube and other services during political rally|date=12 February 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=13 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapatilla.com/2019/02/12/netblocks-denuncia-bloqueos-youtube-durante-manifestacion-12-feb/|title=NetBlocks denuncia bloqueos a YouTube para censurar las manifestaciones de Guaid\u00f3 este #12Feb|date=12 February 2019|website=[[La Patilla]]|language=es-ES|access-date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|18\n|Guaid\u00f3's speech<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/youtube-and-google-services-restricted-in-venezuela-as-guaido-speaks-v7yN4EAq|title=YouTube and Google services restricted in Venezuela as Guaid\u00f3 speaks|date=18 February 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|22\n|Venezuela Aid Live and joint press conference of Guaid\u00f3 and the presidents of Chile, Colombia and Paraguay<ref name=\"netblocksVAL\" />\n|-\n|23\n|Guaid\u00f3 and Duque's speech<ref name=\"netblocks23f\">{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/web-platforms-blocked-in-venezuela-colombia-border-standoff-4JBQzYyo|title=Web platforms blocked in Venezuela-Colombia border standoff|date=23 February 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|24\n|Guaid\u00f3's reception in Bogot\u00e1 to attend Lima Group session<ref name=\"netblocks23f\" />\n|-\n|25\n|Pence's speech addressing Lima Group<ref name=\"netblocks23f\" />\n|-\n|27\n|National Assembly session<ref name=\"twitterblocked\">{{Cite web|url=https://netblocks.org/reports/twitter-blocked-in-venezuela-noy9d4B3|title=Twitter blocked in Venezuela|date=27 February 2019|website=NetBlocks|access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |March\n|6\n|National Assembly session (20 hours)<ref name=\"disruptionrecord\" /><ref name=\"elnacional0704\" />\n|-\n|28\n|Guaid\